WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.806 --> 00:00:05.000
RICK DOBLIN: Yeah,
thank you, thank you.

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:06.140
Well, welcome everybody.

00:00:06.140 --> 00:00:09.190
Thank you for coming today.

00:00:09.190 --> 00:00:10.780
By way of
introduction, I'll just

00:00:10.780 --> 00:00:17.820
say that when I was
18 years old, in 1971,

00:00:17.820 --> 00:00:19.920
I started taking LSD.

00:00:19.920 --> 00:00:23.960
And I was also a Vietnam
War draft resistor,

00:00:23.960 --> 00:00:26.110
I was in the last
year of the lottery,

00:00:26.110 --> 00:00:30.430
and I kind of identified myself
as a counterculture, drug-using

00:00:30.430 --> 00:00:32.950
criminal.

00:00:32.950 --> 00:00:37.540
And so my arc of my life has
been to try to undo that.

00:00:37.540 --> 00:00:39.500
I don't really want
to be a criminal,

00:00:39.500 --> 00:00:42.130
I don't really want
to be counterculture,

00:00:42.130 --> 00:00:45.020
but I do really want
to be a drug user.

00:00:45.020 --> 00:00:48.010
So how do we do that
in our current society?

00:00:48.010 --> 00:00:52.470
So I've had sort of two
strands of training.

00:00:52.470 --> 00:00:55.400
One strand has been in
psychedelic psychotherapy,

00:00:55.400 --> 00:00:57.510
and so I've trained
with Dr. Stanislav

00:00:57.510 --> 00:01:01.930
Grof, who's the world's
leading LSD researcher.

00:01:01.930 --> 00:01:05.220
He's in his 80s now, but he
did work in Prague, and then

00:01:05.220 --> 00:01:10.170
at Johns Hopkins in the '50s,
'60s, and '70s, early '70s.

00:01:10.170 --> 00:01:13.030
And so I've trained with him
in the holotropic breath work.

00:01:13.030 --> 00:01:16.360
And so I wanted
to be a therapist,

00:01:16.360 --> 00:01:18.190
a psychedelic
psychotherapist, and that's

00:01:18.190 --> 00:01:20.930
where I was headed
for about 16 years.

00:01:20.930 --> 00:01:24.760
And then when I
graduated college in '87,

00:01:24.760 --> 00:01:28.900
after dropping out for 10 years
from trying to integrate my LSD

00:01:28.900 --> 00:01:32.430
experiences, I couldn't really
get into any graduate schools,

00:01:32.430 --> 00:01:34.525
because psychedelic
research was shut down.

00:01:34.525 --> 00:01:36.150
So I couldn't get
into graduate schools

00:01:36.150 --> 00:01:38.160
for a clinical
psychology PhD program,

00:01:38.160 --> 00:01:40.410
because whenever I told
them I wanted to do MDMA,

00:01:40.410 --> 00:01:42.670
they were like, well, maybe
they're somewhere else

00:01:42.670 --> 00:01:45.110
you would be more comfortable.

00:01:45.110 --> 00:01:47.400
So then I realized
that the politics was

00:01:47.400 --> 00:01:50.810
in the way of the science,
and I felt like, OK,

00:01:50.810 --> 00:01:52.880
I really need to shift gears.

00:01:52.880 --> 00:01:55.350
I actually was sort of stuck.

00:01:55.350 --> 00:01:57.400
I didn't know what to
do, and I smoked some pot

00:01:57.400 --> 00:02:00.300
and thought about it from
a different perspective.

00:02:00.300 --> 00:02:04.400
And then I thought, yes, OK,
I have a pattern in my life,

00:02:04.400 --> 00:02:06.560
I want too much too soon.

00:02:06.560 --> 00:02:09.740
And I thought, OK,
here I want the science

00:02:09.740 --> 00:02:12.200
but the politics is in the
way, so then I should maybe

00:02:12.200 --> 00:02:13.590
study the politics.

00:02:13.590 --> 00:02:15.290
So I thought, where
could I do that?

00:02:15.290 --> 00:02:18.060
And I had read an interview
with a fellow named

00:02:18.060 --> 00:02:20.011
Mark Kleiman, who was
a professor at Harvard

00:02:20.011 --> 00:02:21.510
at the Kennedy
School of Government,

00:02:21.510 --> 00:02:25.270
and in the interview, he
had mentioned a lawsuit

00:02:25.270 --> 00:02:27.550
that I'd been involved
with against the DEA trying

00:02:27.550 --> 00:02:29.320
to protect the
therapeutic use of MDMA.

00:02:29.320 --> 00:02:31.820
So I contacted him
and I said, would you

00:02:31.820 --> 00:02:33.910
be my mentor if I could get in?

00:02:33.910 --> 00:02:35.090
And he said yes.

00:02:35.090 --> 00:02:40.072
So I've had one strand of
training in public policy,

00:02:40.072 --> 00:02:42.280
so I have a Master's and
PhD from the Kennedy School,

00:02:42.280 --> 00:02:46.450
and I feel like that's
doing psychotherapy

00:02:46.450 --> 00:02:49.350
for sick public policies.

00:02:49.350 --> 00:02:52.420
So it's a combination of
individual psychotherapy

00:02:52.420 --> 00:02:54.110
and sort of collective
psychotherapy,

00:02:54.110 --> 00:02:56.980
and my sort of career
goal-- I'm 62 now,

00:02:56.980 --> 00:02:58.800
I'm still not quite
doing what I exactly

00:02:58.800 --> 00:03:02.200
want to do-- is to become
a psychedelic therapist

00:03:02.200 --> 00:03:07.270
full-time, and we're predicting
that that may be possible

00:03:07.270 --> 00:03:09.700
starting around 2021.

00:03:09.700 --> 00:03:13.650
So that's by way
of introduction.

00:03:13.650 --> 00:03:18.070
This, as you may see,
is the MDMA molecule

00:03:18.070 --> 00:03:19.770
in the Google Doodle there.

00:03:19.770 --> 00:03:22.286
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:22.286 --> 00:03:23.910
One day we hope that
we'll actually see

00:03:23.910 --> 00:03:25.328
that on the Google homepage.

00:03:25.328 --> 00:03:27.420
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:27.420 --> 00:03:30.790
If we succeed, maybe
that will happen.

00:03:30.790 --> 00:03:33.680
So I'm just going to briefly
talk about why this matters,

00:03:33.680 --> 00:03:35.592
and that's about
mystical experiences

00:03:35.592 --> 00:03:36.550
and cultural evolution.

00:03:36.550 --> 00:03:38.091
And then I'll talk
about the strategy

00:03:38.091 --> 00:03:41.670
to get there, which is
nonprofit MDMA PTSD research.

00:03:41.670 --> 00:03:43.730
And then I'll talk about
Burning Man just a bit,

00:03:43.730 --> 00:03:46.827
about how we really ease
cultural transformations,

00:03:46.827 --> 00:03:48.660
and how that's played
a role, and what we're

00:03:48.660 --> 00:03:52.380
trying to do at Burning Man.

00:03:52.380 --> 00:03:54.840
So I have previously
given a Google Tech

00:03:54.840 --> 00:03:58.230
Talk at the Mountain View
campus six years ago--

00:03:58.230 --> 00:04:01.550
bit more than six years ago--
and I watched it in preparation

00:04:01.550 --> 00:04:03.180
for this talk.

00:04:03.180 --> 00:04:06.240
And it was really
interesting to watch,

00:04:06.240 --> 00:04:08.530
because at the time
that I gave that talk,

00:04:08.530 --> 00:04:11.750
we had not really gotten the
data from any of our studies.

00:04:11.750 --> 00:04:14.847
We were sort of talking
about what I thought

00:04:14.847 --> 00:04:15.930
was going to be happening.

00:04:15.930 --> 00:04:19.680
And now, six years later,
we're at the conclusion

00:04:19.680 --> 00:04:23.347
of an international series
of phase two pilot studies,

00:04:23.347 --> 00:04:24.430
and we have a lot of data.

00:04:24.430 --> 00:04:27.410
So I will be sharing
some data with you today.

00:04:27.410 --> 00:04:30.091
And in preparation
for the talk, I

00:04:30.091 --> 00:04:31.590
was trying to think
about, you know,

00:04:31.590 --> 00:04:34.400
I am interested in cultural
change, social evolution,

00:04:34.400 --> 00:04:36.390
and so I started
thinking, what is Google

00:04:36.390 --> 00:04:42.480
doing in the way of long-shot
projects, or moonshot projects?

00:04:42.480 --> 00:04:44.810
And so I checked on
the website, and saw

00:04:44.810 --> 00:04:49.690
that there's a series kind of
the more wide-ranging moonshot

00:04:49.690 --> 00:04:54.750
projects about life extension,
self-driving cars, drones,

00:04:54.750 --> 00:04:58.350
for wind turbines and
for transporting goods,

00:04:58.350 --> 00:05:00.730
Project Loon on the
internet, Project

00:05:00.730 --> 00:05:04.500
Glass for hands-free
reality displays,

00:05:04.500 --> 00:05:06.510
and artificial neural networks.

00:05:06.510 --> 00:05:08.620
So these were the sort
of moon-shot projects

00:05:08.620 --> 00:05:11.350
that I could see that
Google was involved in.

00:05:11.350 --> 00:05:13.780
And what I noticed, though,
that these are all obviously

00:05:13.780 --> 00:05:16.629
technological projects,
and there is something

00:05:16.629 --> 00:05:18.170
that we're all
struggling with, which

00:05:18.170 --> 00:05:19.850
is the emotions and
the spirituality,

00:05:19.850 --> 00:05:23.210
and sort of the hate at
the heart of many people,

00:05:23.210 --> 00:05:26.230
and the fear, and the
anxieties, and that's

00:05:26.230 --> 00:05:27.390
what really threatens us.

00:05:27.390 --> 00:05:29.810
And how are we going
to really address that?

00:05:29.810 --> 00:05:33.420
So I don't think that there
are technological solutions

00:05:33.420 --> 00:05:34.660
to that.

00:05:34.660 --> 00:05:39.150
And this was sort of highlighted
by Albert Einstein, who

00:05:39.150 --> 00:05:42.310
said, "It has become appallingly
obvious that our technology has

00:05:42.310 --> 00:05:45.014
exceeded our humanity."

00:05:45.014 --> 00:05:46.680
He also said, "The
splitting of the atom

00:05:46.680 --> 00:05:49.260
has changed everything
save our mode of thinking,

00:05:49.260 --> 00:05:52.650
and thus we drift towards
unparalleled catastrophe.

00:05:52.650 --> 00:05:55.670
We shall require a substantially
new manner of thinking

00:05:55.670 --> 00:05:57.660
if mankind is to survive."

00:05:57.660 --> 00:06:00.590
So what is that new
manner of thinking,

00:06:00.590 --> 00:06:02.700
and why is that so important?

00:06:02.700 --> 00:06:05.310
There's a little bit of a
clue in the UNESCO charter,

00:06:05.310 --> 00:06:07.660
which was developed
shortly after World War II.

00:06:07.660 --> 00:06:09.750
"Since wars begin
in the minds of men,

00:06:09.750 --> 00:06:12.580
it is in the minds of men
that the defenses of peace

00:06:12.580 --> 00:06:14.530
must be constructed."

00:06:14.530 --> 00:06:16.610
And what is that?

00:06:16.610 --> 00:06:18.940
How do we build
defences of peace?

00:06:18.940 --> 00:06:21.880
And there is another clue,
speaking about moonshots,

00:06:21.880 --> 00:06:23.800
from Edgar Mitchell.

00:06:23.800 --> 00:06:27.590
And so what he said, looking
back on Earth from space, is,

00:06:27.590 --> 00:06:29.500
"When we see our
fundamental unity

00:06:29.500 --> 00:06:32.560
with the processes of
nature and the functioning

00:06:32.560 --> 00:06:36.650
of the universe-- as I so
vividly saw it from the Apollo

00:06:36.650 --> 00:06:39.370
spacecraft-- the old ways
of thinking and behaving

00:06:39.370 --> 00:06:40.740
will disappear."

00:06:40.740 --> 00:06:44.400
There's something about this
unitive cosmic experience

00:06:44.400 --> 00:06:47.550
that does have
political implications.

00:06:47.550 --> 00:06:51.210
And this for me was really
confirmed in 1983, when

00:06:51.210 --> 00:06:54.260
I read this book
by Robert Mueller

00:06:54.260 --> 00:06:57.390
called "New Genesis-- Shaping
a Global Spirituality."

00:06:57.390 --> 00:06:59.880
And Robert Mueller was the
Assistant Secretary General

00:06:59.880 --> 00:07:00.840
of the United Nations.

00:07:00.840 --> 00:07:02.320
He was like the
mystic at the UN.

00:07:02.320 --> 00:07:04.290
He was there for 40 years.

00:07:04.290 --> 00:07:06.590
He's the one that started
the United Nations

00:07:06.590 --> 00:07:08.750
University for
Peace in Costa Rica

00:07:08.750 --> 00:07:11.800
because Costa Rica
abolished its army.

00:07:11.800 --> 00:07:13.980
And what he was
basically saying here

00:07:13.980 --> 00:07:22.020
is that there is a context
where we have the United

00:07:22.020 --> 00:07:24.430
Nations to mediate
conflicts between countries,

00:07:24.430 --> 00:07:28.510
but really what we have is a lot
of religious-based conflicts.

00:07:28.510 --> 00:07:32.360
And what he basically said is
that mysticism is the antidote

00:07:32.360 --> 00:07:35.710
to fundamentalism, and if we
have this global spirituality,

00:07:35.710 --> 00:07:39.130
people will appreciate
other perspectives

00:07:39.130 --> 00:07:41.210
rather than be scared of them.

00:07:41.210 --> 00:07:44.100
And nowhere in his book, though,
does he mention psychedelics.

00:07:44.100 --> 00:07:48.510
So I contacted him and said,
what about psychedelics,

00:07:48.510 --> 00:07:52.740
and would you help me bring
back psychedelic research?

00:07:52.740 --> 00:07:54.934
And he said yes.

00:07:54.934 --> 00:07:56.350
To my utter
astonishment, he wrote

00:07:56.350 --> 00:07:59.970
me back a handwritten
note, and that started

00:07:59.970 --> 00:08:02.010
a long relationship with him.

00:08:02.010 --> 00:08:06.450
And he eventually helped me
in this global-- World Health

00:08:06.450 --> 00:08:10.030
Organization, when they were
trying to criminalize MDMA.

00:08:10.030 --> 00:08:16.080
And this idea of psychedelics
and mysticism and world peace

00:08:16.080 --> 00:08:18.320
was sort of shockingly--
this is just

00:08:18.320 --> 00:08:21.740
this recent issue of a
journal called "The Optimist."

00:08:21.740 --> 00:08:26.730
The top is "How LSD May Bring
Peace to the Middle East."

00:08:26.730 --> 00:08:30.820
And it turns out this is an
interview with Stan Grof,

00:08:30.820 --> 00:08:32.789
and he's talking
about a conference

00:08:32.789 --> 00:08:35.710
that he wants to organize that
we're talking about working

00:08:35.710 --> 00:08:38.380
on together, that he calls
"A Light from Middle East The

00:08:38.380 --> 00:08:40.690
Common Roots of the
Abrahamic Traditions,"

00:08:40.690 --> 00:08:42.216
Islam, Judaism,
and Christianity.

00:08:42.216 --> 00:08:43.590
And what he wants
to do is really

00:08:43.590 --> 00:08:45.510
bring, again, the
mystics together,

00:08:45.510 --> 00:08:49.010
and help them try to
develop strategies to deal

00:08:49.010 --> 00:08:51.160
with the fundamentalists.

00:08:51.160 --> 00:08:55.380
And what I really was able
to talk to Robert Mueller

00:08:55.380 --> 00:08:58.390
about, and sort of give you
now a little bit of data,

00:08:58.390 --> 00:09:01.200
in a sense, about this
psychedelic mysticism,

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:03.070
is from the Good
Friday experiment.

00:09:03.070 --> 00:09:04.990
This is the best thing
that Timothy Leary ever

00:09:04.990 --> 00:09:06.680
did, in my view.

00:09:06.680 --> 00:09:08.890
He was the faculty sponsor
for this at Harvard.

00:09:08.890 --> 00:09:10.490
It was in 1962.

00:09:10.490 --> 00:09:12.860
And it was a
scientific study trying

00:09:12.860 --> 00:09:16.696
to evaluate whether people with
a religious tradition-- these

00:09:16.696 --> 00:09:18.070
were Christian
divinity students,

00:09:18.070 --> 00:09:21.440
in a religious setting--
whether psilocybin

00:09:21.440 --> 00:09:25.360
mushrooms-- extracted
psilocybin--

00:09:25.360 --> 00:09:29.070
whether that would be promoting
of a mystical experience.

00:09:29.070 --> 00:09:33.770
And so they went into Marsh
Chapel at Boston University,

00:09:33.770 --> 00:09:36.300
and they went through
a Good Friday service,

00:09:36.300 --> 00:09:41.070
and half got psilocybin
pills and half got placebo.

00:09:41.070 --> 00:09:44.760
And this was actually-- they
did it in the downstairs chapel.

00:09:44.760 --> 00:09:47.820
That's me there giving
a little homily.

00:09:47.820 --> 00:09:51.711
And they had 10 people,
as well, that were

00:09:51.711 --> 00:09:52.960
part of the experimental team.

00:09:52.960 --> 00:09:54.834
Half of them got the
psilocybin, half of them

00:09:54.834 --> 00:09:56.810
got the placebo as well.

00:09:56.810 --> 00:09:59.650
And the minister
was Howard Thurman.

00:09:59.650 --> 00:10:02.220
So to give you an idea
of how non-controversial

00:10:02.220 --> 00:10:06.060
this was in 1962, Howard
Thurman was Martin Luther King's

00:10:06.060 --> 00:10:07.030
mentor.

00:10:07.030 --> 00:10:11.520
Martin Luther King got a
PhD at Boston University.

00:10:11.520 --> 00:10:14.220
He was an incredible,
dynamic preacher,

00:10:14.220 --> 00:10:16.460
and he agreed to let
a bunch of people

00:10:16.460 --> 00:10:18.660
take psilocybin in
the basement while he

00:10:18.660 --> 00:10:20.920
was doing Good Friday services.

00:10:20.920 --> 00:10:24.060
And it was piped in, and we
have the original sermons

00:10:24.060 --> 00:10:24.660
that he gave.

00:10:24.660 --> 00:10:26.070
They're up on our website.

00:10:26.070 --> 00:10:27.280
They were saved.

00:10:27.280 --> 00:10:31.650
And how do you tell if somebody
has a mystical experience?

00:10:31.650 --> 00:10:33.820
So Walter Pahnke
spent a year surveying

00:10:33.820 --> 00:10:36.560
the religious literature, and
he developed a questionnaire

00:10:36.560 --> 00:10:39.520
of the mystical experience,
and this was extracted

00:10:39.520 --> 00:10:41.020
from the different religions.

00:10:41.020 --> 00:10:44.320
So he wanted to do it where
even though it was Good Friday,

00:10:44.320 --> 00:10:46.590
and it didn't have
anything to do with Jesus,

00:10:46.590 --> 00:10:48.480
or any particular
religious tradition.

00:10:48.480 --> 00:10:52.210
This was sort of the essence
of the mystical experience.

00:10:52.210 --> 00:10:54.842
And the key part was
the sense of unity.

00:10:54.842 --> 00:10:57.050
That's what Edgar Mitchell
was talking about as well,

00:10:57.050 --> 00:11:00.360
this internal and external,
that it's all together.

00:11:00.360 --> 00:11:02.600
We get there from
quantum physics,

00:11:02.600 --> 00:11:05.250
in some ways, that a lot
of what we're understanding

00:11:05.250 --> 00:11:08.140
is how we are all
intimately connected.

00:11:08.140 --> 00:11:09.930
There's this feeling
of this transcendence

00:11:09.930 --> 00:11:11.750
of time and space.

00:11:11.750 --> 00:11:14.220
There is a sense of sacredness.

00:11:14.220 --> 00:11:16.770
There is a sense of
objective reality.

00:11:16.770 --> 00:11:18.599
There's a deeply
felt positive mood,

00:11:18.599 --> 00:11:20.890
and there's this sense that
it's beyond words, that you

00:11:20.890 --> 00:11:22.600
can't really put it into words.

00:11:22.600 --> 00:11:25.250
This is like an
MC Escher drawing,

00:11:25.250 --> 00:11:26.900
just doesn't make sense.

00:11:26.900 --> 00:11:29.080
And then there was
various questions

00:11:29.080 --> 00:11:31.170
that operationalized
these definitions,

00:11:31.170 --> 00:11:33.800
and then you could get a
numerical score on how deep

00:11:33.800 --> 00:11:36.100
was your mystical experience.

00:11:36.100 --> 00:11:39.090
And I ended up realizing
in the middle '80s,

00:11:39.090 --> 00:11:41.530
when I wanted to do psychedelic
research, when I needed

00:11:41.530 --> 00:11:44.020
to do a thesis for
my undergraduate,

00:11:44.020 --> 00:11:46.510
is that psychedelic
research was blocked--

00:11:46.510 --> 00:11:48.990
and it had been blocked
for almost two decades--

00:11:48.990 --> 00:11:55.160
but the real issue with mystical
experiences in the literature

00:11:55.160 --> 00:11:56.190
is the fruits test.

00:11:56.190 --> 00:11:57.820
It's not how you
describe it, it's

00:11:57.820 --> 00:11:59.720
what are the fruits
of the experience?

00:11:59.720 --> 00:12:03.700
Are they positive,
are they opening?

00:12:03.700 --> 00:12:08.332
And so I realized that I could
go back and ask the people that

00:12:08.332 --> 00:12:09.790
were in the study
what they thought

00:12:09.790 --> 00:12:11.800
were the long-term
effects on their lives.

00:12:11.800 --> 00:12:14.390
And Walter Pahnke, who
had done the experiment,

00:12:14.390 --> 00:12:17.442
actually had died in a scuba
diving accident in 1971.

00:12:17.442 --> 00:12:18.900
So I'm convinced
that he would have

00:12:18.900 --> 00:12:22.420
done this long-term follow-up
if he would have been alive.

00:12:22.420 --> 00:12:25.650
So I was able to, through
all sorts of detective work,

00:12:25.650 --> 00:12:29.820
find 19-- identify 19
out of the 20 people,

00:12:29.820 --> 00:12:31.610
and I interviewed 16 of them.

00:12:31.610 --> 00:12:34.510
And one of them
told me this thing,

00:12:34.510 --> 00:12:37.110
"We took such an infinitesimal
amount of psilocybin,

00:12:37.110 --> 00:12:40.470
and yet it connected
me to infinity."

00:12:40.470 --> 00:12:44.180
So I re-administered the same
questionnaires to these people,

00:12:44.180 --> 00:12:45.900
and there's a lot
of data, but I just

00:12:45.900 --> 00:12:49.850
wanted to show you
that this point here.

00:12:49.850 --> 00:12:53.370
60 or above was considered
a full mystical experience.

00:12:53.370 --> 00:12:56.830
And so this was
the original data,

00:12:56.830 --> 00:13:00.320
and then this one here is my
long-term, 25 years later.

00:13:00.320 --> 00:13:02.610
And you can see
the placebo group.

00:13:02.610 --> 00:13:05.800
It's almost identical,
even after 25 years.

00:13:05.800 --> 00:13:09.290
And this is in the midst of the
Reagan escalation of the drug

00:13:09.290 --> 00:13:12.450
war, so if there was
any time, culturally,

00:13:12.450 --> 00:13:14.980
for people to
disavow the validity

00:13:14.980 --> 00:13:16.620
of their prior
psychedelic experience,

00:13:16.620 --> 00:13:17.620
this would have been it.

00:13:17.620 --> 00:13:19.590
And yet they affirmed it.

00:13:19.590 --> 00:13:22.660
And what, more importantly,
they said to me--

00:13:22.660 --> 00:13:24.640
and this was through all
of these interviews--

00:13:24.640 --> 00:13:27.800
that the mystical experience
had political implications,

00:13:27.800 --> 00:13:30.470
and it fundamentally
increased their tolerance

00:13:30.470 --> 00:13:32.680
of other religions, it
deepened their equanimity

00:13:32.680 --> 00:13:36.410
in the face of life crises,
it promoted greater solidarity

00:13:36.410 --> 00:13:39.260
and identification with foreign
peoples, minorities, women--

00:13:39.260 --> 00:13:41.720
this was all men in this
experiment-- and nature,

00:13:41.720 --> 00:13:43.272
and it reduced
their fear of death.

00:13:43.272 --> 00:13:44.730
So we're starting
to see that there

00:13:44.730 --> 00:13:48.580
is some kind of long-term effect
from this mystical experience.

00:13:48.580 --> 00:13:51.980
The modern research that is
taking place with psilocybin

00:13:51.980 --> 00:13:55.860
here in New York at
NYU, at Johns Hopkins,

00:13:55.860 --> 00:14:02.000
and also at UCLA, has
been going on for a while.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.160
And what Roland
Griffiths has done

00:14:04.160 --> 00:14:08.172
is he's sort of updated the Good
Friday experiment, in a sense.

00:14:08.172 --> 00:14:10.130
What he's done is he's
taken people who are not

00:14:10.130 --> 00:14:13.010
religious professionals,
and he has taken them

00:14:13.010 --> 00:14:15.100
in a setting that is
not a religious setting,

00:14:15.100 --> 00:14:17.940
in a clinical setting,
given them psilocybin,

00:14:17.940 --> 00:14:20.740
and find that they still
have mystical experiences.

00:14:20.740 --> 00:14:23.590
And many of them rank them as
the top five most important

00:14:23.590 --> 00:14:25.630
experiences of their life.

00:14:25.630 --> 00:14:28.360
They also have done these
personality tests with people,

00:14:28.360 --> 00:14:31.650
and personality is
considered to be pretty fixed

00:14:31.650 --> 00:14:34.640
once you're an adult, and
what they found surprised

00:14:34.640 --> 00:14:37.360
them, is that there
was long-term changes

00:14:37.360 --> 00:14:39.170
in people's
personalities related

00:14:39.170 --> 00:14:41.000
to the mystical experience.

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:42.860
And that was in the
dimension of openness.

00:14:42.860 --> 00:14:45.990
And this is-- Katherine MacLean
has written this paper she

00:14:45.990 --> 00:14:48.160
was part of their team.

00:14:48.160 --> 00:14:51.940
"Mystical experiences occasioned
by the hallucinogen psilocybin

00:14:51.940 --> 00:14:53.900
lead to increases
in the personality

00:14:53.900 --> 00:14:55.074
domain of openness."

00:14:55.074 --> 00:14:56.990
And again, this is
starting to be a little bit

00:14:56.990 --> 00:15:00.690
more modern evidence, again,
about how social change could

00:15:00.690 --> 00:15:04.380
be impacted by these
psychedelic-induced mystical

00:15:04.380 --> 00:15:05.810
experiences.

00:15:05.810 --> 00:15:08.330
They use the NEO
Personality Inventory.

00:15:08.330 --> 00:15:10.190
There's five
domains, six facets,

00:15:10.190 --> 00:15:12.270
but the openness to
experience is the one

00:15:12.270 --> 00:15:13.700
that was really changed.

00:15:13.700 --> 00:15:16.150
I think when you talk about
rigidity and fundamentalism,

00:15:16.150 --> 00:15:18.410
people are not open
to new experiences,

00:15:18.410 --> 00:15:20.290
they're not open to new ideas.

00:15:20.290 --> 00:15:22.690
And that's what she
found was changed.

00:15:22.690 --> 00:15:25.670
And her paper said
this. "Consistent

00:15:25.670 --> 00:15:28.270
with participant claims
of hallucinogen-occasioned

00:15:28.270 --> 00:15:31.760
increases in aesthetic
appreciation, imagination,

00:15:31.760 --> 00:15:35.440
creativity, we found significant
increases in Openness following

00:15:35.440 --> 00:15:37.287
a high-dose psilocybin session.

00:15:37.287 --> 00:15:38.870
And what I've written
down below there

00:15:38.870 --> 00:15:42.880
is that we have found similar
changes in openness on the NEO

00:15:42.880 --> 00:15:45.950
with our MDMA research with
post-traumatic stress disorder

00:15:45.950 --> 00:15:47.990
patients, and we're
working on getting

00:15:47.990 --> 00:15:50.110
those papers published as well.

00:15:50.110 --> 00:15:52.820
So there does seem to
be something going on.

00:15:52.820 --> 00:15:57.880
And it's also, when we talk
about spirituality, we all

00:15:57.880 --> 00:16:01.240
should have the right to
explore our own consciousness,

00:16:01.240 --> 00:16:04.540
to explore our connection
to the religion,

00:16:04.540 --> 00:16:06.100
and to our meaning
of the universe.

00:16:06.100 --> 00:16:12.320
It's not just idle curiosity,
it's a fundamental human right.

00:16:12.320 --> 00:16:15.170
And this was an article
from the MAPS Bulletin.

00:16:15.170 --> 00:16:17.480
This is the first
articulation by a donor,

00:16:17.480 --> 00:16:21.120
by a foundation, that their
support of our research

00:16:21.120 --> 00:16:22.850
was part of their
human rights mission.

00:16:22.850 --> 00:16:25.016
This is the Pritzker, Nick
and Susan Pritzker Family

00:16:25.016 --> 00:16:28.930
Foundation, from the family
that own the Hyatt hotels.

00:16:28.930 --> 00:16:30.790
And their foundation
is focused-- The Libra

00:16:30.790 --> 00:16:32.730
Foundation-- on human rights.

00:16:32.730 --> 00:16:34.540
And so, there is
this sense that this

00:16:34.540 --> 00:16:36.680
is a broader issue
as well, in terms

00:16:36.680 --> 00:16:38.500
of our own personal freedoms.

00:16:38.500 --> 00:16:40.570
And how do we get there though?

00:16:40.570 --> 00:16:42.412
Because we're stuck
with prohibition,

00:16:42.412 --> 00:16:43.370
at least at the moment.

00:16:43.370 --> 00:16:45.060
Now, we see that
prohibition is eroding.

00:16:45.060 --> 00:16:46.940
It's a great thing
to see the rise

00:16:46.940 --> 00:16:49.860
of the interest in
marijuana legalization

00:16:49.860 --> 00:16:52.910
and the concerns about
over-incarceration.

00:16:52.910 --> 00:16:56.660
And here is the
strategy that explains

00:16:56.660 --> 00:17:00.110
why trying to do psychedelic
psychotherapy research

00:17:00.110 --> 00:17:03.440
is really part of changing
cultural attitudes.

00:17:03.440 --> 00:17:07.339
This is a chart showing the
attitudes of American voters

00:17:07.339 --> 00:17:11.140
over the last 40 plus years on
the legalization of marijuana.

00:17:11.140 --> 00:17:13.950
And what it shows is
that, starting in 1970,

00:17:13.950 --> 00:17:14.890
it's down around 12%.

00:17:14.890 --> 00:17:16.859
And just a few years
ago, it crossed

00:17:16.859 --> 00:17:19.099
the line and more
than 50% of the public

00:17:19.099 --> 00:17:21.050
is in favor of legalization.

00:17:21.050 --> 00:17:23.406
But what's most interesting
to me about this

00:17:23.406 --> 00:17:27.280
is this long period
here from around '76

00:17:27.280 --> 00:17:31.130
to around '96 here-- almost
20 years-- where it's flat.

00:17:31.130 --> 00:17:32.450
Nothing's going on.

00:17:32.450 --> 00:17:35.070
And somehow, things
start changing again.

00:17:35.070 --> 00:17:37.620
And they start moving up.

00:17:37.620 --> 00:17:40.630
And what is it that happens
around 1996 that starts

00:17:40.630 --> 00:17:42.130
to change people's attitudes?

00:17:42.130 --> 00:17:44.040
Medical marijuana.

00:17:44.040 --> 00:17:48.210
California and Arizona passed
medical marijuana laws in 1996.

00:17:48.210 --> 00:17:52.270
And polling has been
done-- exit polling,

00:17:52.270 --> 00:17:54.947
after people have voted
on marijuana initiatives

00:17:54.947 --> 00:17:55.780
in different states.

00:17:55.780 --> 00:17:59.570
And what we've found is that
the single most important factor

00:17:59.570 --> 00:18:01.490
about whether
somebody is in favor

00:18:01.490 --> 00:18:03.700
of the legalization
of marijuana is not

00:18:03.700 --> 00:18:05.251
if they use
marijuana themselves.

00:18:05.251 --> 00:18:06.750
You would think
that marijuana users

00:18:06.750 --> 00:18:07.875
don't want to be criminals.

00:18:07.875 --> 00:18:11.050
But it's if they know a medical
marijuana patient personally.

00:18:11.050 --> 00:18:12.480
That changes their attitudes.

00:18:12.480 --> 00:18:13.960
Because there's so
much propaganda.

00:18:13.960 --> 00:18:15.460
People don't know
what to believe.

00:18:15.460 --> 00:18:16.960
Even people that
smoke pot sometimes

00:18:16.960 --> 00:18:18.590
think it's not good
to make it legal.

00:18:18.590 --> 00:18:21.130
But this is the theory
of social change

00:18:21.130 --> 00:18:24.250
here, that the medicalization
changes attitudes,

00:18:24.250 --> 00:18:26.730
brings a more accurate
risk-benefit analysis

00:18:26.730 --> 00:18:27.280
to people.

00:18:27.280 --> 00:18:28.780
They know people
who have benefited.

00:18:28.780 --> 00:18:30.340
And then, they start
changing their attitudes

00:18:30.340 --> 00:18:31.410
towards legalization.

00:18:31.410 --> 00:18:35.664
So that has led us now to this
idea of, how do we do this?

00:18:35.664 --> 00:18:38.080
And we're thinking about, how
do we integrate psychedelics

00:18:38.080 --> 00:18:40.340
into our culture?

00:18:40.340 --> 00:18:42.290
And I want to point
out that it's not new.

00:18:42.290 --> 00:18:44.820
If we go to the beginnings
of Western culture

00:18:44.820 --> 00:18:47.250
with the Greeks, the
longest running mystery

00:18:47.250 --> 00:18:50.250
ceremonies that we're
aware of, for 2,000 years,

00:18:50.250 --> 00:18:52.050
was the Eleusinian Mysteries.

00:18:52.050 --> 00:18:55.800
And they were wiped out by
the Catholic Church in 396.

00:18:55.800 --> 00:18:58.650
And Albert Hoffman,
who invented LSD

00:18:58.650 --> 00:19:00.390
and first synthesized
psilocybin,

00:19:00.390 --> 00:19:05.300
did some studies with
Greek scholars and others.

00:19:05.300 --> 00:19:08.300
And they noticed that, in
the Eleusinian Mysteries,

00:19:08.300 --> 00:19:09.994
they drink a potion
called kykeon.

00:19:09.994 --> 00:19:11.910
And then, they walk a
certain number of hours.

00:19:11.910 --> 00:19:13.520
And then, they
have this ceremony.

00:19:13.520 --> 00:19:16.560
And they've timed how long
it takes to do the walk

00:19:16.560 --> 00:19:19.440
and how long it takes what
they know was in the potion.

00:19:19.440 --> 00:19:22.130
And it's at the
peak of the trip,

00:19:22.130 --> 00:19:24.630
you're at this place
for the ceremony.

00:19:24.630 --> 00:19:28.280
So that's from our
Western culture.

00:19:28.280 --> 00:19:29.910
And when we think
about the Greeks

00:19:29.910 --> 00:19:32.590
and we think about the people
that started our culture-- so

00:19:32.590 --> 00:19:35.120
Plato, Aristotle, Pythagoras,
Cicero, Sophocles,

00:19:35.120 --> 00:19:37.710
they all participated in
these mystery ceremonies.

00:19:37.710 --> 00:19:41.320
So even though it's
1,600 plus years ago,

00:19:41.320 --> 00:19:43.980
it's not something new that
we're trying to bring back.

00:19:43.980 --> 00:19:47.220
And there is a lot of-- I
can understand a bit how

00:19:47.220 --> 00:19:51.660
religion and superstition has
a lot of misinformation in it.

00:19:51.660 --> 00:19:53.650
And so we did have
to separate a bit,

00:19:53.650 --> 00:19:57.260
so the rational mind could move
ahead unfettered by all this.

00:19:57.260 --> 00:20:00.160
But now, we need to
bring it together again.

00:20:00.160 --> 00:20:05.950
So I happened to be at Google in
December out in Mountain View.

00:20:05.950 --> 00:20:07.980
And I was walking actually.

00:20:07.980 --> 00:20:09.710
One of our donors is there.

00:20:09.710 --> 00:20:11.950
And before I left, I
wanted to get some Google

00:20:11.950 --> 00:20:13.724
Frisbees for my kids.

00:20:13.724 --> 00:20:15.390
And we were walking
to the Google store.

00:20:15.390 --> 00:20:18.370
And we passed this
sign on the campus.

00:20:18.370 --> 00:20:19.391
And I did a double take.

00:20:19.391 --> 00:20:20.890
You can't see what
I was looking at.

00:20:20.890 --> 00:20:22.770
But here, I noticed
that there was a Google

00:20:22.770 --> 00:20:26.100
Department of World Peace.

00:20:26.100 --> 00:20:28.690
And it was room 2021.

00:20:28.690 --> 00:20:31.540
And for us, that's meaningful.

00:20:31.540 --> 00:20:34.490
So the ultimate moonshot,
obviously, is world peace.

00:20:34.490 --> 00:20:36.900
I'm really glad to see
that Google is involved.

00:20:36.900 --> 00:20:38.460
It turns out, as
far as we can tell--

00:20:38.460 --> 00:20:40.510
and I'm sort of embarrassed
to say that I was in a hurry.

00:20:40.510 --> 00:20:41.926
So I didn't go to
see if there was

00:20:41.926 --> 00:20:43.830
that room that actually exists.

00:20:43.830 --> 00:20:47.830
But the MAPS donor is
going to check it out.

00:20:47.830 --> 00:20:49.570
But I've searched
on the internet.

00:20:49.570 --> 00:20:51.340
It seems to be a joke.

00:20:51.340 --> 00:20:52.390
But I hope it's not.

00:20:52.390 --> 00:20:55.730
And I did think that the
2021 room was incredible.

00:20:55.730 --> 00:20:57.370
Because our drug
development plan

00:20:57.370 --> 00:21:00.140
shows that MDMA will
be approved by the FDA,

00:21:00.140 --> 00:21:02.660
if all goes to plan, in 2021.

00:21:02.660 --> 00:21:06.030
So maybe there is some secret
Google plan to support MAPS

00:21:06.030 --> 00:21:10.490
and to make psychedelics
into legal medicines.

00:21:10.490 --> 00:21:11.800
And it makes sense.

00:21:11.800 --> 00:21:14.130
Because this is an article
from the "Washington Post."

00:21:14.130 --> 00:21:17.180
They talked about MDMA
as the peace drug.

00:21:17.180 --> 00:21:19.600
So OK, that fits with the
Department of World Peace.

00:21:19.600 --> 00:21:21.750
And here we are in the Pentagon.

00:21:21.750 --> 00:21:25.200
So actually, this is Dr. Richard
Rockefeller, Michael Mithoefer,

00:21:25.200 --> 00:21:26.762
our lead psychiatrist.

00:21:26.762 --> 00:21:28.470
And you're not supposed
to take pictures.

00:21:28.470 --> 00:21:31.290
So I did it pretty quickly.

00:21:31.290 --> 00:21:34.356
But we were speaking with
senior members of the Navy--

00:21:34.356 --> 00:21:36.230
the Navy Surgeon General,
Assistant Secretary

00:21:36.230 --> 00:21:38.240
of the Navy, and
others-- about trying

00:21:38.240 --> 00:21:43.300
to do MDMA research
with Marines with PTSD.

00:21:43.300 --> 00:21:46.200
Eventually, they decided they
would be much more comfortable

00:21:46.200 --> 00:21:48.550
if we started working
with veterans instead

00:21:48.550 --> 00:21:50.200
of active-duty soldiers.

00:21:50.200 --> 00:21:53.660
But we are working on
the MDMA peace plan.

00:21:53.660 --> 00:21:56.850
And this is what we're
hoping will happen in 2021,

00:21:56.850 --> 00:22:00.020
that we'll be able to sell--
GMP means Good Manufacturing

00:22:00.020 --> 00:22:01.950
Practices-- medical-grade MDMA.

00:22:01.950 --> 00:22:04.550
We'll have programs
to train therapists.

00:22:04.550 --> 00:22:09.490
And also, we're going to have a
network of psychedelic therapy

00:22:09.490 --> 00:22:10.202
clinics.

00:22:10.202 --> 00:22:12.160
So one day, you'll be
able to go to Google Maps

00:22:12.160 --> 00:22:14.880
and press, where is the
nearest psychedelic clinic?

00:22:14.880 --> 00:22:16.010
And you'll get--

00:22:16.010 --> 00:22:18.620
And we anticipate that,
actually, the model here

00:22:18.620 --> 00:22:20.060
is the hospice movement.

00:22:20.060 --> 00:22:22.670
In 1974 was the first hospice.

00:22:22.670 --> 00:22:26.210
30 years later, there was 3,500
of them, all over America.

00:22:26.210 --> 00:22:30.340
So it takes 20, 30 years for
new cultural things to roll out.

00:22:30.340 --> 00:22:31.760
But we anticipate
that there will

00:22:31.760 --> 00:22:33.644
be these psychedelic centers.

00:22:33.644 --> 00:22:35.060
And they will
eventually be places

00:22:35.060 --> 00:22:36.601
where people go to
therapy but, also,

00:22:36.601 --> 00:22:39.920
can go to have these
personal growth experiences.

00:22:39.920 --> 00:22:43.670
So OK, how do we now
medicalize psychedelics?

00:22:43.670 --> 00:22:45.140
And the journey
actually, for me,

00:22:45.140 --> 00:22:46.700
began from a political
point of view

00:22:46.700 --> 00:22:50.740
in 1984, when the DEA first
tried to criminalize MDMA.

00:22:50.740 --> 00:22:55.180
From the middle '70s to the
early '80s, MDMA was legal.

00:22:55.180 --> 00:22:57.284
It was used under
the code name Adam.

00:22:57.284 --> 00:22:59.700
It was distributed through
underground psychedelic therapy

00:22:59.700 --> 00:23:00.200
networks.

00:23:00.200 --> 00:23:03.142
Over a half a million doses
were used in that context.

00:23:03.142 --> 00:23:04.600
And the government
had no knowledge

00:23:04.600 --> 00:23:05.580
that that was going on.

00:23:05.580 --> 00:23:08.045
But some of those people
took MDMA, said, wow,

00:23:08.045 --> 00:23:08.920
this is a great drug.

00:23:08.920 --> 00:23:10.290
More people should have it.

00:23:10.290 --> 00:23:11.940
It should be more
widely available.

00:23:11.940 --> 00:23:13.540
And we're going to
name it Ecstasy,

00:23:13.540 --> 00:23:15.230
and we're going to
sell it in public.

00:23:15.230 --> 00:23:18.061
And that was, eventually,
obviously going

00:23:18.061 --> 00:23:19.060
to doom the whole thing.

00:23:19.060 --> 00:23:21.220
Because it was done in
more public settings,

00:23:21.220 --> 00:23:23.490
people knew about it, and
it was the Reagan era.

00:23:23.490 --> 00:23:26.920
So in the summer of '84, the
DEA moved to criminalize.

00:23:26.920 --> 00:23:29.140
And we had been
preparing for years ahead

00:23:29.140 --> 00:23:30.890
in anticipation of this.

00:23:30.890 --> 00:23:34.250
And we had great DC law firms
working pro bono for us.

00:23:34.250 --> 00:23:36.410
So I walked to the
DEA headquarters.

00:23:36.410 --> 00:23:40.271
So that's the picture
of me spying on the DEA,

00:23:40.271 --> 00:23:41.910
right before I
walked in the door

00:23:41.910 --> 00:23:45.090
to totally surprise
them with this petition,

00:23:45.090 --> 00:23:46.530
which they eventually granted.

00:23:46.530 --> 00:23:49.120
And we did get a DEA
administrative law judge

00:23:49.120 --> 00:23:49.770
lawsuit.

00:23:49.770 --> 00:23:50.800
We won the case.

00:23:50.800 --> 00:23:54.170
The judge said, MDMA should
be therapeutically available

00:23:54.170 --> 00:23:55.130
still.

00:23:55.130 --> 00:23:58.180
And the head of the DEA
administrator rejected it.

00:23:58.180 --> 00:23:59.770
We sued him in
the appeals court.

00:23:59.770 --> 00:24:00.700
We won a couple times.

00:24:00.700 --> 00:24:02.940
Eventually, the DEA
lawyers figured out

00:24:02.940 --> 00:24:06.940
how to reject our application
and still satisfy the courts.

00:24:06.940 --> 00:24:08.440
And then, it felt
to me like there's

00:24:08.440 --> 00:24:11.630
no way else but through
medicine, through the FDA.

00:24:11.630 --> 00:24:13.870
So in '86 is when
I started MAPS.

00:24:13.870 --> 00:24:17.882
And our strategy-- I call
it the Aikido strategy.

00:24:17.882 --> 00:24:19.340
Because what you're
doing is you're

00:24:19.340 --> 00:24:22.472
using the momentum of your
opponent against them.

00:24:22.472 --> 00:24:24.430
You're not actually even
directly hurting them.

00:24:24.430 --> 00:24:27.050
And in this case,
what we're using

00:24:27.050 --> 00:24:29.480
is the fact that
MDMA, LSD, marijuana,

00:24:29.480 --> 00:24:30.730
these are all demonized drugs.

00:24:30.730 --> 00:24:32.460
And governments
all over the world

00:24:32.460 --> 00:24:35.610
have spent hundreds of millions
of dollars trying to show

00:24:35.610 --> 00:24:37.490
what's bad with these drugs.

00:24:37.490 --> 00:24:39.100
Now, some of their
interpretations

00:24:39.100 --> 00:24:40.370
are a little bit skewed.

00:24:40.370 --> 00:24:42.610
But the point is that
there is an enormous amount

00:24:42.610 --> 00:24:45.090
of information on this drug.

00:24:45.090 --> 00:24:49.200
If you go to Medline and
you put in MDMA or Ecstasy,

00:24:49.200 --> 00:24:52.950
there's over 5,100
papers on MDMA or Ecstasy

00:24:52.950 --> 00:24:55.920
at a estimated cost
of over $300 million.

00:24:55.920 --> 00:24:57.826
And the risks are
well-characterized.

00:24:57.826 --> 00:24:59.450
We know about the
mechanisms of action.

00:24:59.450 --> 00:25:01.400
And over 1,100 people
have been given

00:25:01.400 --> 00:25:03.560
MDMA in clinical settings.

00:25:03.560 --> 00:25:06.680
Only about 150 by us, a
little bit less than that.

00:25:06.680 --> 00:25:08.330
And the rest are
by people trying

00:25:08.330 --> 00:25:10.540
to understand risks and
mechanisms of action,

00:25:10.540 --> 00:25:12.770
things like that, that
we've not had to pay for.

00:25:12.770 --> 00:25:15.140
But there's a lot of
safety information.

00:25:15.140 --> 00:25:18.650
And now, is this
really so demonized?

00:25:18.650 --> 00:25:20.880
Last Sunday, in the
"New York Times,"

00:25:20.880 --> 00:25:22.980
the "Sunday Review"
section, the cover article

00:25:22.980 --> 00:25:25.800
was about "A Drug to Cure Fear."

00:25:25.800 --> 00:25:27.810
And this was the
illustration that they

00:25:27.810 --> 00:25:29.090
used in the "New York Times."

00:25:29.090 --> 00:25:32.980
And it was about propranolol,
which is a beta blocker.

00:25:32.980 --> 00:25:34.490
It reduces anxiety.

00:25:34.490 --> 00:25:38.200
And they tried to have
people talk a little bit

00:25:38.200 --> 00:25:41.810
about their trauma, while under
the influence of propranolol

00:25:41.810 --> 00:25:44.300
and see if that would
help them get over--

00:25:44.300 --> 00:25:47.360
every time they remember
it again-- being fearful.

00:25:47.360 --> 00:25:51.810
And this article said, "A
2015 review of PTSD treatment

00:25:51.810 --> 00:25:54.340
studies published in
'Biological Psychology'

00:25:54.340 --> 00:25:56.040
found that propranolol
administered

00:25:56.040 --> 00:25:57.800
with six brief
trauma reactivation

00:25:57.800 --> 00:26:01.800
sessions significantly
improved PTSD symptoms

00:26:01.800 --> 00:26:03.850
compared with a placebo."

00:26:03.850 --> 00:26:05.500
So they're starting
to show evidence

00:26:05.500 --> 00:26:08.040
of this drug-assisted
psychotherapy.

00:26:08.040 --> 00:26:13.730
But MDMA is likely to work a
lot better than propranolol

00:26:13.730 --> 00:26:15.270
in these models.

00:26:15.270 --> 00:26:17.650
And at the end of the
article, Richard Friedman--

00:26:17.650 --> 00:26:21.550
who's here in New York-- the
final paragraph of the article

00:26:21.550 --> 00:26:23.580
was, "I see nothing
wrong with doing

00:26:23.580 --> 00:26:26.720
all we can to rid ourselves
of pathological anxiety,

00:26:26.720 --> 00:26:30.530
including using drugs to
alter our painful memories."

00:26:30.530 --> 00:26:32.570
He's not actually a fan of MDMA.

00:26:32.570 --> 00:26:34.470
So he would probably
be upset if he

00:26:34.470 --> 00:26:37.870
saw that I was using him
to endorse MDMA research.

00:26:37.870 --> 00:26:41.890
But the principle is this
idea of psychotherapy

00:26:41.890 --> 00:26:44.790
combined with a drug is
getting more and more accepted.

00:26:44.790 --> 00:26:47.507
And people see that as
potentially helpful.

00:26:47.507 --> 00:26:49.340
And the public attitudes
have been changing.

00:26:49.340 --> 00:26:52.110
This was about 15 years ago.

00:26:52.110 --> 00:26:56.820
This was the first image in the
media of positive connections

00:26:56.820 --> 00:26:58.050
to Ecstasy.

00:26:58.050 --> 00:26:59.560
This was an Israeli newspaper.

00:26:59.560 --> 00:27:01.170
We had a project in Israel.

00:27:01.170 --> 00:27:03.700
And this was, like, the
helicopters in the background,

00:27:03.700 --> 00:27:05.260
like a soldier in
a blood Red Sea,

00:27:05.260 --> 00:27:09.730
holding onto an Ecstasy
pill as a life saver.

00:27:09.730 --> 00:27:12.440
So when you see the
images in media,

00:27:12.440 --> 00:27:14.310
this really started
saying, wow, this

00:27:14.310 --> 00:27:17.200
is the first positive one ever.

00:27:17.200 --> 00:27:21.830
More recently, Oprah-- who
to her shame, I would say,

00:27:21.830 --> 00:27:25.930
10 years before this, 2001,
she had a show on MDMA.

00:27:25.930 --> 00:27:29.040
And she showed doctored,
fake images of MDMA

00:27:29.040 --> 00:27:31.940
supposedly causing
holes in the brain.

00:27:31.940 --> 00:27:33.880
They just took a SPECT scan.

00:27:33.880 --> 00:27:35.380
And they just said,
every place that

00:27:35.380 --> 00:27:36.838
has activity below
a certain level,

00:27:36.838 --> 00:27:39.970
they'll just show as a hole.

00:27:39.970 --> 00:27:42.860
So in 2001, though, "O
Magazine" published an article

00:27:42.860 --> 00:27:43.690
about MDMA.

00:27:43.690 --> 00:27:46.170
This was the illustration
that they used.

00:27:46.170 --> 00:27:49.170
And it was, Can a single
pill heal your pain?

00:27:49.170 --> 00:27:52.780
So this is, of course,
propaganda on the other side.

00:27:52.780 --> 00:27:54.684
But we'll accept it.

00:27:54.684 --> 00:27:56.300
[LAUGHTER]

00:27:56.300 --> 00:27:58.360
And this, more recently,
was in October.

00:27:58.360 --> 00:28:01.070
This is the "Canadian
Medical Association Journal."

00:28:01.070 --> 00:28:02.880
This is all about
psychedelic drugs.

00:28:02.880 --> 00:28:04.460
And again, you're
starting to see,

00:28:04.460 --> 00:28:07.470
we've had incredibly good
publicity over the last 10,

00:28:07.470 --> 00:28:12.430
15 years as culture is ready
to look at psychedelics again.

00:28:12.430 --> 00:28:13.434
And so, how do we do it?

00:28:13.434 --> 00:28:14.850
The first thing
that we need to do

00:28:14.850 --> 00:28:18.630
is we need to get
medical-grade MDMA.

00:28:18.630 --> 00:28:23.000
I had MDMA manufactured in
1985 by Dave Nichols at Purdue

00:28:23.000 --> 00:28:26.010
University for our research.

00:28:26.010 --> 00:28:30.090
It was $4,000 for
one kilogram of MDMA.

00:28:30.090 --> 00:28:32.070
MDMA is an incredibly
stable molecule.

00:28:32.070 --> 00:28:37.590
So 31 years later now, we're
using that exact same MDMA

00:28:37.590 --> 00:28:39.050
in our research.

00:28:39.050 --> 00:28:40.070
And he had a good yield.

00:28:40.070 --> 00:28:41.360
He had more than a kilogram.

00:28:41.360 --> 00:28:43.960
We have 960 grams left.

00:28:43.960 --> 00:28:45.760
But it's not medical-grade.

00:28:45.760 --> 00:28:49.250
It's not something that
we can use in Phase 3.

00:28:49.250 --> 00:28:52.500
So we did a international search
for pharmaceutical companies.

00:28:52.500 --> 00:28:54.700
And we made a deal
with this Shasun.

00:28:54.700 --> 00:28:58.080
They're making us one kilogram
of medical-grade MDMA.

00:28:58.080 --> 00:29:02.260
To make it and put it
into capsules is $400,000.

00:29:02.260 --> 00:29:05.180
And it's not any better or
purer than what we already have.

00:29:05.180 --> 00:29:07.960
It's just more documentation,
more paperwork,

00:29:07.960 --> 00:29:09.730
more standardization.

00:29:09.730 --> 00:29:11.199
So this is the first step.

00:29:11.199 --> 00:29:13.490
And the production-- I just
got an e-mail the other day

00:29:13.490 --> 00:29:15.140
that they've finally
got permission

00:29:15.140 --> 00:29:17.790
from the home office in
England to buy the precursors.

00:29:17.790 --> 00:29:20.900
So we're on the road
to having the world's

00:29:20.900 --> 00:29:22.640
supply of medical-grade MDMA.

00:29:22.640 --> 00:29:25.749
AUDIENCE: Where is all the
MDMA on the street coming from?

00:29:25.749 --> 00:29:26.540
RICK DOBLIN: Well--

00:29:26.540 --> 00:29:27.720
AUDIENCE: Can you
repeat the question.

00:29:27.720 --> 00:29:29.928
RICK DOBLIN: So the question
is, where's all the MDMA

00:29:29.928 --> 00:29:31.640
on the street coming from?

00:29:31.640 --> 00:29:33.448
Well, if I knew, I
wouldn't tell you.

00:29:33.448 --> 00:29:35.080
[LAUGHTER]

00:29:35.080 --> 00:29:37.170
But it's coming from
underground chemists.

00:29:37.170 --> 00:29:39.714
Some of them are really
interested in purity.

00:29:39.714 --> 00:29:41.380
And others are just
interested in money.

00:29:41.380 --> 00:29:45.160
So there's Erowid, which is
a website about psychedelics.

00:29:45.160 --> 00:29:46.650
We started a
project-- actually, it

00:29:46.650 --> 00:29:51.330
was the number 10 employee
of Microsoft-- Bob Wallace

00:29:51.330 --> 00:29:54.450
said, a lot of this MDMA that's
being sold as Ecstasy is not

00:29:54.450 --> 00:29:55.680
really MDMA.

00:29:55.680 --> 00:29:57.910
So we have an Ecstasy
pill-testing program.

00:29:57.910 --> 00:30:00.100
He donated over $100,000.

00:30:00.100 --> 00:30:05.540
And it turns out that more than
half of the Ecstasy or Molly

00:30:05.540 --> 00:30:07.721
doesn't have any
MDMA in it at all.

00:30:07.721 --> 00:30:09.220
So you have to be
really wary of it.

00:30:09.220 --> 00:30:12.720
But there are people that supply
underground therapy networks.

00:30:12.720 --> 00:30:15.020
And so, there is some pure
stuff out there as well.

00:30:15.020 --> 00:30:16.570
But it's all
underground chemists.

00:30:16.570 --> 00:30:21.054
The same place that LSD
comes from and all of that.

00:30:21.054 --> 00:30:21.970
So we're getting that.

00:30:21.970 --> 00:30:23.690
And then, just to give you
a little bit of a sense.

00:30:23.690 --> 00:30:25.190
What is our therapy method?

00:30:25.190 --> 00:30:27.470
It's not one-dose miracle-cure.

00:30:27.470 --> 00:30:32.220
The therapy method is basically
a 3 and 1/2 month process.

00:30:32.220 --> 00:30:34.530
And it's weekly
non-drug psychotherapy.

00:30:34.530 --> 00:30:36.120
Those are the vertical lines.

00:30:36.120 --> 00:30:39.660
And the triangles are
the MDMA sessions.

00:30:39.660 --> 00:30:44.370
So one month apart, there is
three of these MDMA sessions

00:30:44.370 --> 00:30:45.860
in a 3 and 1/2 month process.

00:30:45.860 --> 00:30:49.480
So a lot of emphasis on
preparation, on integration.

00:30:49.480 --> 00:30:51.550
And in our current
studies, we break the blind

00:30:51.550 --> 00:30:52.949
after the second session.

00:30:52.949 --> 00:30:54.740
And then, those people
that had the placebo

00:30:54.740 --> 00:30:56.704
could go through it
again as open label.

00:30:56.704 --> 00:30:58.370
Meaning, they know
they're getting MDMA.

00:30:58.370 --> 00:31:03.450
So it's both comparing people
against a controlled group.

00:31:03.450 --> 00:31:05.590
And then, also people
are their own controls,

00:31:05.590 --> 00:31:07.050
once we give them MDMA.

00:31:07.050 --> 00:31:08.430
So that's the basic experiment.

00:31:08.430 --> 00:31:11.840
And we have developed
a treatment manual

00:31:11.840 --> 00:31:15.240
to try to standardize, what
is our therapeutic approach?

00:31:15.240 --> 00:31:17.305
For research,
everything that you can,

00:31:17.305 --> 00:31:18.730
you need to standardize.

00:31:18.730 --> 00:31:24.000
This is based on a non-directive
approach from LSD research.

00:31:24.000 --> 00:31:28.590
We are now getting ready to
negotiate with FDA and what's

00:31:28.590 --> 00:31:31.800
called the End-of-Phase 2
meeting, where you summarize

00:31:31.800 --> 00:31:33.600
all of your data, and
you submit the data,

00:31:33.600 --> 00:31:36.130
and you ask for permission
to go to Phase 3.

00:31:36.130 --> 00:31:39.060
Phase 3 is what really counts
to make a drug into a medicine.

00:31:39.060 --> 00:31:42.290
Phase 2 are these small,
pilot, exploratory studies.

00:31:42.290 --> 00:31:47.230
So we have 105 people
so far with PTSD

00:31:47.230 --> 00:31:48.690
that have been in our studies.

00:31:48.690 --> 00:31:51.150
And we have data that I'll show
you from around 95 of them.

00:31:51.150 --> 00:31:52.830
We're wrapping up
all of these studies.

00:31:52.830 --> 00:31:55.220
We hope, in April,
to submit to FDA.

00:31:55.220 --> 00:31:57.610
And the first thing
that FDA wants to know

00:31:57.610 --> 00:31:59.270
is about the safety.

00:31:59.270 --> 00:32:01.610
So in the scientific
literature, the concern

00:32:01.610 --> 00:32:05.610
is that Ecstasy users might
have reduced cognitive functions

00:32:05.610 --> 00:32:06.370
in certain ways.

00:32:06.370 --> 00:32:08.330
And some studies
have shown that.

00:32:08.330 --> 00:32:11.360
But it's really hard to
piece apart Ecstasy users.

00:32:11.360 --> 00:32:14.500
They've done all
these other drugs.

00:32:14.500 --> 00:32:15.244
They don't sleep.

00:32:15.244 --> 00:32:16.410
There's all sorts of things.

00:32:16.410 --> 00:32:20.320
So is it really from MDMA?

00:32:20.320 --> 00:32:23.760
So we've done
neurocognitive studies

00:32:23.760 --> 00:32:26.510
with people in our
clinical contexts.

00:32:26.510 --> 00:32:28.890
And we've combined two of the
different studies together.

00:32:28.890 --> 00:32:30.820
You need to have two
independent studies

00:32:30.820 --> 00:32:34.470
to satisfy the FDA that it's
not just a fluke from one study.

00:32:34.470 --> 00:32:38.730
And so, the blue lines
are before the experiment

00:32:38.730 --> 00:32:39.417
at baseline.

00:32:39.417 --> 00:32:40.750
And then, the red line is after.

00:32:40.750 --> 00:32:42.240
So what you can
see is that there

00:32:42.240 --> 00:32:45.240
is no change in
neurocognitive functioning,

00:32:45.240 --> 00:32:48.130
either from the active
doses or the placebo

00:32:48.130 --> 00:32:50.150
or the comparator,
which is low doses.

00:32:50.150 --> 00:32:52.670
So we have a very
good safety profile,

00:32:52.670 --> 00:32:56.310
in terms of
neurocognitive function.

00:32:56.310 --> 00:32:58.180
This is, now, body temperature.

00:32:58.180 --> 00:33:00.180
You may have heard about
how people go to raves,

00:33:00.180 --> 00:33:02.430
they dance all night,
they overeat and die.

00:33:02.430 --> 00:33:04.340
And that does
happen occasionally.

00:33:04.340 --> 00:33:05.850
It's called hyperthermia.

00:33:05.850 --> 00:33:07.680
And so, we monitor
everybody's temperature.

00:33:07.680 --> 00:33:11.020
And so, people's temperature
tends to go up during the day.

00:33:11.020 --> 00:33:13.170
And we give MDMA at
10:00 in the morning.

00:33:13.170 --> 00:33:15.710
And by 6:00 at night, it's
an eight-hour session.

00:33:15.710 --> 00:33:18.280
Then, people can rest.

00:33:18.280 --> 00:33:19.360
And the therapists leave.

00:33:19.360 --> 00:33:22.550
And so, this is the temperature.

00:33:22.550 --> 00:33:24.510
And it doesn't go
up hardly at all.

00:33:24.510 --> 00:33:25.230
There is no risk.

00:33:25.230 --> 00:33:27.890
This is the variation of bars
so you can see the range.

00:33:27.890 --> 00:33:31.140
But there is no concern
about temperature overheating

00:33:31.140 --> 00:33:32.390
in a clinical setting.

00:33:32.390 --> 00:33:33.360
This is blood pressure.

00:33:33.360 --> 00:33:35.050
MDMA increases blood pressure.

00:33:35.050 --> 00:33:38.220
You can see, again here,
that there is minimal rises.

00:33:38.220 --> 00:33:39.720
And this is the range.

00:33:39.720 --> 00:33:41.860
That's systolic, and
here is diastolic.

00:33:41.860 --> 00:33:43.500
Again, that's the range.

00:33:43.500 --> 00:33:46.590
So we've got really good
safety data on neurocognitive,

00:33:46.590 --> 00:33:49.510
on temperature,
on blood pressure.

00:33:49.510 --> 00:33:51.680
And then, what about
psychological effects?

00:33:51.680 --> 00:33:55.160
So the kind of adverse effects
that people are reporting

00:33:55.160 --> 00:33:56.790
are anxiety, jaw clenching.

00:33:56.790 --> 00:33:58.960
And this is displayed
from low dose

00:33:58.960 --> 00:34:01.750
to the full dose--
125 milligrams.

00:34:01.750 --> 00:34:04.510
So jaw clenching is one of
the big ones, no appetite.

00:34:04.510 --> 00:34:07.060
The reason I've highlighted the
ones under the 30 milligram,

00:34:07.060 --> 00:34:08.690
is just to show
that muscle tension,

00:34:08.690 --> 00:34:11.999
fatigue happened at the
low doses more even,

00:34:11.999 --> 00:34:13.290
sometimes, than the high doses.

00:34:13.290 --> 00:34:15.719
So none of this is problematic.

00:34:15.719 --> 00:34:18.230
There has not been a single
drug-related serious adverse

00:34:18.230 --> 00:34:21.620
event in all of these 1,100
people, not just our studies.

00:34:21.620 --> 00:34:23.380
So we have conclusively,
in our view--

00:34:23.380 --> 00:34:25.429
and we believe the
FDA will agree--

00:34:25.429 --> 00:34:26.845
have demonstrated safety.

00:34:26.845 --> 00:34:28.969
And they keep giving us
permission to do protocols.

00:34:28.969 --> 00:34:30.052
So that's another example.

00:34:30.052 --> 00:34:32.368
As do regulators
around the world.

00:34:32.368 --> 00:34:34.409
So now, I'm going to switch
to the efficacy data.

