00:34:54.489 --> 00:34:57.340
And she said, "since I've
been cured of PTSD, I only

00:34:57.340 --> 00:35:00.900
suffer from one thing with
PTSD, and that's the survivor's

00:35:00.900 --> 00:35:04.390
guilt. I got heled, while I am
surrounded by people who don't

00:35:04.390 --> 00:35:05.860
know that they have any hope.

00:35:05.860 --> 00:35:09.020
Who, until this medicine is
approved, probably don't."

00:35:09.020 --> 00:35:11.832
There are a lot of good
therapies for PTSD.

00:35:11.832 --> 00:35:13.290
But there's large
numbers of people

00:35:13.290 --> 00:35:15.590
who are chronic
treatment resistant PTSD.

00:35:15.590 --> 00:35:17.410
Right now, the
Department of Defense

00:35:17.410 --> 00:35:21.920
is giving disability payments
to 600,000 vets for PTSD

00:35:21.920 --> 00:35:26.122
at a cost of around $6 billion
a year, which is outrageous.

00:35:26.122 --> 00:35:27.330
And that's going to continue.

00:35:27.330 --> 00:35:30.030
So when we think about the
cost of war, $6 billion a year.

00:35:30.030 --> 00:35:30.997
That's going up.

00:35:30.997 --> 00:35:32.580
These people, a lot
of them are young.

00:35:32.580 --> 00:35:35.650
They're going to be living
for another 40, 50 years.

00:35:35.650 --> 00:35:39.310
And so, the enormous burden
of PTSD on our society

00:35:39.310 --> 00:35:41.070
and on those people
that have it.

00:35:41.070 --> 00:35:42.500
So this is a summary chart.

00:35:42.500 --> 00:35:46.530
The key point is that we know
about statistical significance.

00:35:46.530 --> 00:35:49.887
But with clinical
research, more and more,

00:35:49.887 --> 00:35:51.720
people have moved to
looking at effect size.

00:35:51.720 --> 00:35:53.520
The FDA really looks
at effect size.

00:35:53.520 --> 00:35:55.680
Because you can have
statistically significant

00:35:55.680 --> 00:36:00.250
results, even if you have
clinically marginally

00:36:00.250 --> 00:36:02.250
significant effects.

00:36:02.250 --> 00:36:05.990
So effect size is about the
magnitude of the effect.

00:36:05.990 --> 00:36:10.870
And we have got the
good fortune of the FDA

00:36:10.870 --> 00:36:15.010
director of psychiatry products,
who's recently retired.

00:36:15.010 --> 00:36:17.550
And he reviewed our protocols
for the last 15 years.

00:36:17.550 --> 00:36:19.591
And he says, he likes the
way we're doing things.

00:36:19.591 --> 00:36:21.870
So he's now acting
as our consultant.

00:36:21.870 --> 00:36:24.770
So we now have hired.

00:36:24.770 --> 00:36:27.820
Basically, MAPS is a nonprofit
pharmaceutical company,

00:36:27.820 --> 00:36:29.810
trying to develop
psychedelics into medicines.

00:36:29.810 --> 00:36:31.560
So that's how I think
of what we're doing.

00:36:31.560 --> 00:36:34.450
We're primarily doing FDA
drug development research.

00:36:34.450 --> 00:36:38.930
And what he said is that the
drugs that the FDA approves,

00:36:38.930 --> 00:36:41.490
they almost never cure
anything in psychiatry.

00:36:41.490 --> 00:36:43.120
They're all palliative
for symptoms.

00:36:43.120 --> 00:36:45.830
And they almost all have
a very small effect size

00:36:45.830 --> 00:36:47.570
of around 0.3.

00:36:47.570 --> 00:36:51.420
And so, what we have
is a large effect size.

00:36:51.420 --> 00:36:54.115
And these are their effects.

00:36:54.115 --> 00:36:54.740
They're over 1.

00:36:54.740 --> 00:36:58.290
So other than just
one small study, where

00:36:58.290 --> 00:37:00.260
some of the placebo
people actually did better

00:37:00.260 --> 00:37:04.980
than the full-dose MDMA people,
we have large effect sizes.

00:37:04.980 --> 00:37:08.770
And then, when you combine it
all, this is our combined data.

00:37:08.770 --> 00:37:10.790
We've just got these
the last few days.

00:37:10.790 --> 00:37:13.170
So what it just shows
is the baseline,

00:37:13.170 --> 00:37:14.950
then at the primary
endpoint, which is

00:37:14.950 --> 00:37:17.060
the end of the blinded portion.

00:37:17.060 --> 00:37:18.940
And then, the people
at the top in the blue,

00:37:18.940 --> 00:37:20.690
which are in the
placebo group, we

00:37:20.690 --> 00:37:23.520
give them the chance
to get MDMA afterwards.

00:37:23.520 --> 00:37:26.830
So the 12-month follow-up
is after everybody

00:37:26.830 --> 00:37:28.470
has gotten MDMA.

00:37:28.470 --> 00:37:29.970
And you can see
that they all end up

00:37:29.970 --> 00:37:31.880
pretty much the same place.

00:37:31.880 --> 00:37:33.950
And that there's a
significant difference, when

00:37:33.950 --> 00:37:38.130
we look at the primary
outcome blinded portion of it,

00:37:38.130 --> 00:37:40.000
and a large effect size.

00:37:40.000 --> 00:37:42.500
This is just to show you another
way of looking at the data.

00:37:42.500 --> 00:37:45.510
The comparator doses-- we
tried, for double-blind,

00:37:45.510 --> 00:37:48.800
to use low dose MDMA
compared with full dose.

00:37:48.800 --> 00:37:52.730
And so, there is a little bit
of a decrease in their scores.

00:37:52.730 --> 00:37:55.330
It's called the CAPS scores,
the Clinician Administered PTSD

00:37:55.330 --> 00:37:56.240
Scale.

00:37:56.240 --> 00:38:00.100
That's the measure developed by
the VA, used by FDA to evaluate

00:38:00.100 --> 00:38:01.950
the severity of PTSD.

00:38:01.950 --> 00:38:04.480
And the active doses
are, again, much larger.

00:38:04.480 --> 00:38:07.170
So we believe that, based
on this data-- and this

00:38:07.170 --> 00:38:09.630
is putting it all
together from the baseline

00:38:09.630 --> 00:38:10.720
to the 12-month follow-up.

00:38:10.720 --> 00:38:13.810
The point is that the
benefits last over time.

00:38:13.810 --> 00:38:15.630
They don't just fade away.

00:38:15.630 --> 00:38:18.000
It's not just the
psychedelic afterglow

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:20.090
and, then, it fades
as reality comes back.

00:38:20.090 --> 00:38:22.500
There's something
fundamentally changed.

00:38:22.500 --> 00:38:24.740
And that's what's
really exciting to us.

00:38:24.740 --> 00:38:27.050
And it's not after daily MDMA.

00:38:27.050 --> 00:38:29.740
It's only after a few doses.

00:38:29.740 --> 00:38:30.930
Some people do relapse.

00:38:30.930 --> 00:38:32.760
This is a slide of
just three people.

00:38:32.760 --> 00:38:36.990
The FDA gave us permission to
give one more session of MDMA

00:38:36.990 --> 00:38:39.870
to people that had their
PTSD symptoms come back

00:38:39.870 --> 00:38:41.330
after the year follow-up.

00:38:41.330 --> 00:38:44.520
And of these three people, when
we gave them an additional MDMA

00:38:44.520 --> 00:38:46.670
session, their
symptoms all went down.

00:38:46.670 --> 00:38:49.574
The red line there is
moderate to severe PTSD.

00:38:49.574 --> 00:38:51.740
That's what they had to be
above to be in our study.

00:38:51.740 --> 00:38:52.921
They're all below that.

00:38:52.921 --> 00:38:54.920
And then, at the one-year
follow-up, two of them

00:38:54.920 --> 00:38:56.600
were still lower at that.

00:38:56.600 --> 00:38:57.980
But one had relapsed.

00:38:57.980 --> 00:39:00.220
So I don't want to give the
wrong impression that you

00:39:00.220 --> 00:39:01.810
give MDMA to somebody,
it fixes them

00:39:01.810 --> 00:39:03.280
for the rest of their life.

00:39:03.280 --> 00:39:05.520
People who have
PTSD have usually

00:39:05.520 --> 00:39:06.610
had a history of trauma.

00:39:06.610 --> 00:39:08.910
They're more vulnerable
to more life shocks.

00:39:08.910 --> 00:39:10.160
But it does last.

00:39:10.160 --> 00:39:12.450
And the averages that
I've showed you before

00:39:12.450 --> 00:39:15.500
include the people
that relapsed.

00:39:15.500 --> 00:39:17.160
This was now the study in vets.

00:39:17.160 --> 00:39:20.360
The point here I want to
make is that we were shocked,

00:39:20.360 --> 00:39:24.170
in that we were doing 30
milligrams, 75 milligrams, 125

00:39:24.170 --> 00:39:24.670
milligrams.

00:39:24.670 --> 00:39:27.080
And I thought that there would
be a dose response curve.

00:39:27.080 --> 00:39:30.980
But it turned out that the
red is the 75 milligrams.

00:39:30.980 --> 00:39:34.950
The medium dose actually did
better than the full dose.

00:39:34.950 --> 00:39:38.320
And when those of us--
underground therapists

00:39:38.320 --> 00:39:41.380
tend to work at the
125 milligrams dose.

00:39:41.380 --> 00:39:43.430
This was a real surprise.

00:39:43.430 --> 00:39:48.410
And we also are starting to
understand research and memory

00:39:48.410 --> 00:39:49.710
reconsolidation.

00:39:49.710 --> 00:39:51.690
And so, this helps
us understand that.

00:39:51.690 --> 00:39:55.530
That when you have a memory
and you bring it back,

00:39:55.530 --> 00:39:57.520
it's not like a book
and you look at it

00:39:57.520 --> 00:39:58.440
and you put the
book on the shelf.

00:39:58.440 --> 00:39:59.856
You sort have to
reprint the book.

00:39:59.856 --> 00:40:01.650
You reconsolidate the memory.

00:40:01.650 --> 00:40:04.140
And so, if you have
a traumatic memory

00:40:04.140 --> 00:40:07.080
and it's associated
with fear, if you're

00:40:07.080 --> 00:40:09.460
recalling the memory
when you're feeling safe,

00:40:09.460 --> 00:40:11.690
when you reconsolidate
the memory,

00:40:11.690 --> 00:40:15.240
you have memory for the
autobiographical details.

00:40:15.240 --> 00:40:18.050
But the emotional
tone is now overlaid

00:40:18.050 --> 00:40:20.190
by that feeling of safety.

00:40:20.190 --> 00:40:23.370
And at the 75 milligrams,
people stay more grounded.

00:40:23.370 --> 00:40:25.070
They stay more in
their biography.

00:40:25.070 --> 00:40:28.890
At the 125, people have
more spiritual feelings.

00:40:28.890 --> 00:40:33.710
They have more body feelings
that are pleasurable.

00:40:33.710 --> 00:40:37.760
But they're a little bit
away from their trauma.

00:40:37.760 --> 00:40:39.340
So this is helping
us to understand.

00:40:39.340 --> 00:40:41.548
And now, the Rockefeller
family-- Richard Rockefeller

00:40:41.548 --> 00:40:42.950
was a major ally.

00:40:42.950 --> 00:40:45.030
He died in a plane crash.

00:40:45.030 --> 00:40:48.040
To honor Richard, his
family has funded research

00:40:48.040 --> 00:40:50.640
at Rockefeller University
with animal models,

00:40:50.640 --> 00:40:53.050
looking at MDMA and
memory reconsolidation.

00:40:53.050 --> 00:40:55.160
So we're starting
to understand that.

00:40:55.160 --> 00:40:57.370
This is to show-- this
is the depression data.

00:40:57.370 --> 00:40:59.320
So a lot of people
that have PTSD also

00:40:59.320 --> 00:41:00.920
have co-morbid depression.

00:41:00.920 --> 00:41:04.670
And depression also
goes down as well.

00:41:04.670 --> 00:41:08.980
And this is, now, a key
point-- difference between MDMA

00:41:08.980 --> 00:41:11.850
and psychedelic research
with classic psychedelics.

00:41:11.850 --> 00:41:14.280
What has found from
the '50s and '60s

00:41:14.280 --> 00:41:20.270
and is also the case with
the current research--

00:41:20.270 --> 00:41:22.460
with psilocybin
and cancer patients

00:41:22.460 --> 00:41:26.830
or with psilocybin and
alcoholics or tobacco addicts--

00:41:26.830 --> 00:41:28.620
the depth of the
mystical experience

00:41:28.620 --> 00:41:30.970
is correlated with
therapeutic outcome,

00:41:30.970 --> 00:41:34.810
the loss of the fear of death,
the sense of connection.

00:41:34.810 --> 00:41:37.150
We do the same
questionnaire with MDMA.

00:41:37.150 --> 00:41:40.400
And so this shows that
the mystical experience

00:41:40.400 --> 00:41:43.480
is pretty good, pretty
strong, even with people

00:41:43.480 --> 00:41:46.050
who get MDMA, which
is not known for being

00:41:46.050 --> 00:41:50.180
as spiritual in some ways
as the classic psychedelics.

00:41:50.180 --> 00:41:52.000
And so, we show that
the comparator doses

00:41:52.000 --> 00:41:55.410
have relatively low scores
on the mystical experience

00:41:55.410 --> 00:41:56.000
questionnaire.

00:41:56.000 --> 00:41:57.900
The active doses
are much fuller.

00:41:57.900 --> 00:41:59.960
But this is the key
point here, which

00:41:59.960 --> 00:42:03.270
is this is a chart
showing the relationship

00:42:03.270 --> 00:42:08.100
between the drop in CAPS scores
and the mystical experience.

00:42:08.100 --> 00:42:08.860
And it's flat.

00:42:08.860 --> 00:42:11.250
What we're showing is
there is no correlation

00:42:11.250 --> 00:42:14.780
between mystical experience
here and therapeutic outcome.

00:42:14.780 --> 00:42:16.160
That's the
fundamental difference

00:42:16.160 --> 00:42:18.560
between what we're doing
in the psilocybin research.

00:42:18.560 --> 00:42:22.170
And that also explains that we
have a non-directive approach.

00:42:22.170 --> 00:42:24.900
We're not trying to help people
have a mystical experience.

00:42:24.900 --> 00:42:28.600
We're trying to just help them
emerge whatever is coming up

00:42:28.600 --> 00:42:30.310
and, particularly,
focusing on peacefully

00:42:30.310 --> 00:42:32.460
looking at their trauma.

00:42:32.460 --> 00:42:35.220
So what we've learned is, there
is safety in clinical settings,

00:42:35.220 --> 00:42:38.980
the large effect size, the
cause of the PTSD is irrelevant.

00:42:38.980 --> 00:42:41.690
We've worked with veterans,
firefighters, police officers,

00:42:41.690 --> 00:42:45.860
women survivors of child sexual
abuse, adult rape and assault,

00:42:45.860 --> 00:42:47.310
workplace accidents.

00:42:47.310 --> 00:42:49.640
The cause of the PTSD
doesn't really matter.

00:42:49.640 --> 00:42:51.220
We can enroll anybody.

00:42:51.220 --> 00:42:54.450
And that the double-blind--
as you should not

00:42:54.450 --> 00:42:57.500
be surprised to learn--
didn't really work.

00:42:57.500 --> 00:42:59.840
People can tell if they've
got an inactive placebo--

00:42:59.840 --> 00:43:01.120
[LAUGHTER]

00:43:01.120 --> 00:43:02.290
--or if they get the MDMA.

00:43:02.290 --> 00:43:06.610
But the low doses of MDMA had
an anti-therapeutic effect.

00:43:06.610 --> 00:43:08.100
So that was a big problem.

00:43:08.100 --> 00:43:10.340
And what our FDA
consultant has said

00:43:10.340 --> 00:43:13.702
is that we can't really solve
the double-blind problem

00:43:13.702 --> 00:43:15.160
and that we'll just
have to compare

00:43:15.160 --> 00:43:16.230
with an inactive placebo.

00:43:16.230 --> 00:43:18.770
So what we're
proposing is Phase 3

00:43:18.770 --> 00:43:21.410
will be inactive
placebo with therapy.

00:43:21.410 --> 00:43:24.810
So it's basically therapy
with an inactive placebo

00:43:24.810 --> 00:43:26.280
versus therapy with MDMA.

00:43:26.280 --> 00:43:27.920
That's going to
be our comparison.

00:43:27.920 --> 00:43:31.740
We'll use three MDMA sessions
with 12 non-drug sessions.

00:43:31.740 --> 00:43:35.110
We'll give everybody the
75 milligram dose first.

00:43:35.110 --> 00:43:37.420
And then, on their second
and third sessions,

00:43:37.420 --> 00:43:40.160
we'll have a discussion between
the therapists and patients.

00:43:40.160 --> 00:43:41.820
Do they want to have the same?

00:43:41.820 --> 00:43:43.507
Or do they want to
have it stronger?

00:43:43.507 --> 00:43:44.590
They won't know the doses.

00:43:44.590 --> 00:43:47.256
They won't know even if
they've got the placebo or not.

00:43:47.256 --> 00:43:49.880
But they'll just say, I want it
the same or I want it stronger.

00:43:49.880 --> 00:43:51.004
And that's how we'll do it.

00:43:51.004 --> 00:43:53.370
And then, because the
double-blind problem

00:43:53.370 --> 00:43:55.680
is an issue, what
means more important

00:43:55.680 --> 00:43:57.160
is the independent raters.

00:43:57.160 --> 00:43:59.950
So the therapists don't
say, how are you doing?

00:43:59.950 --> 00:44:01.260
And you're doing much better.

00:44:01.260 --> 00:44:02.468
Because that could be biased.

00:44:02.468 --> 00:44:04.270
So we have a group
of [INAUDIBLE]

00:44:04.270 --> 00:44:07.660
liability-trained
outcome-measure experts.

00:44:07.660 --> 00:44:09.640
And they will do this
all by telemedicine.

00:44:09.640 --> 00:44:13.522
And they'll be randomly assigned
to which person they review.

00:44:13.522 --> 00:44:15.230
So they won't know,
is this the baseline?

00:44:15.230 --> 00:44:16.063
Is this the outcome?

00:44:16.063 --> 00:44:17.554
Is this the 12-month follow-up?

00:44:17.554 --> 00:44:19.720
And this is what we're going
to be proposing to FDA.

00:44:19.720 --> 00:44:22.510
We're anticipating 400
subjects, $22 million.

00:44:22.510 --> 00:44:26.070
And I don't know how
many of you might

00:44:26.070 --> 00:44:27.470
know a program called HSPICE.

00:44:27.470 --> 00:44:32.040
It's used to produce computer
manufacturing computer chips.

00:44:32.040 --> 00:44:36.250
The developers of it--
Ashawna Hailey and Kim Hailey.

00:44:36.250 --> 00:44:38.450
Ashawna was on our
board of directors.

00:44:38.450 --> 00:44:41.710
And after he sold his company,
made a whole bunch of money,

00:44:41.710 --> 00:44:43.980
he went into studying
consciousness

00:44:43.980 --> 00:44:47.290
and did all sorts of stuff, got
very involved in psychedelics.

00:44:47.290 --> 00:44:51.500
He died, left us $5.3
million in his will.

00:44:51.500 --> 00:44:54.150
And we're using that
for the Phase 3 studies.

00:44:54.150 --> 00:44:57.830
And Dr. Bronner's from-- I don't
know how many of you have read

00:44:57.830 --> 00:44:58.600
the label on--

00:44:58.600 --> 00:44:59.580
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:59.580 --> 00:45:00.460
--Dr. Bronner's--

00:45:00.460 --> 00:45:01.425
AUDIENCE: All one.

00:45:01.425 --> 00:45:02.550
RICK DOBLIN: Yeah, all one.

00:45:02.550 --> 00:45:06.260
Dr. Bronner was traumatized
by the Holocaust,

00:45:06.260 --> 00:45:08.150
sort of driven crazy.

00:45:08.150 --> 00:45:10.730
But his thing was we all
need to love each other.

00:45:10.730 --> 00:45:11.530
We're all together.

00:45:11.530 --> 00:45:12.610
We're all one.

00:45:12.610 --> 00:45:16.510
And his grandson, David
Bronner, went to Harvard,

00:45:16.510 --> 00:45:18.730
is a really smart guy and
has built the business up

00:45:18.730 --> 00:45:20.090
with his brother Mike.

00:45:20.090 --> 00:45:23.070
And they are very
charitable oriented.

00:45:23.070 --> 00:45:24.480
It's a benefit corporation.

00:45:24.480 --> 00:45:26.270
David's on our
board of directors.

00:45:26.270 --> 00:45:28.680
They've pledged $1 million
a year for five years,

00:45:28.680 --> 00:45:29.879
starting next year.

00:45:29.879 --> 00:45:31.420
And the reason is
because, this year,

00:45:31.420 --> 00:45:36.370
they want to help legalize
marijuana on the 2016

00:45:36.370 --> 00:45:37.200
elections.

00:45:37.200 --> 00:45:40.620
And one of the
other tech people--

00:45:40.620 --> 00:45:43.060
he wanted to stay
anonymous at the moment--

00:45:43.060 --> 00:45:45.064
has pledged $1 million
after we agree with FDA.

00:45:45.064 --> 00:45:47.230
And I said, why is it that
you want to be anonymous?

00:45:47.230 --> 00:45:48.540
And he said, well,
business reasons.

00:45:48.540 --> 00:45:50.998
And I said, what would it take
for you to not be anonymous?

00:45:50.998 --> 00:45:53.000
He said, if you can
get 1,000 people,

00:45:53.000 --> 00:45:55.550
I would come out
with all of them.

00:45:55.550 --> 00:45:58.280
So if any of you know people
that are ready to come out,

00:45:58.280 --> 00:46:01.630
we're starting to
gather a list of people

00:46:01.630 --> 00:46:03.970
who make contributions that
the world would recognize

00:46:03.970 --> 00:46:05.640
and, then, who would say, yeah.

00:46:05.640 --> 00:46:08.490
Well, psychedelics have
been important in my life.

00:46:08.490 --> 00:46:10.280
Now, what I've
learned more recently

00:46:10.280 --> 00:46:13.740
is that, once you make a drug
into a medicine-- I thought,

00:46:13.740 --> 00:46:15.690
MDMA is in the public domain.

00:46:15.690 --> 00:46:16.690
There is no use patents.

00:46:16.690 --> 00:46:18.150
We actually hired
patent attorneys

00:46:18.150 --> 00:46:20.444
to develop an
anti-patent strategy.

00:46:20.444 --> 00:46:21.610
And I'm actually doing that.

00:46:21.610 --> 00:46:24.680
I'm on the board of directors
of a company that is genetically

00:46:24.680 --> 00:46:27.220
screening marijuana
strains and putting them

00:46:27.220 --> 00:46:30.910
in the public domain, so
nobody could patent them.

00:46:30.910 --> 00:46:33.890
So there will be hundreds
of marijuana strains

00:46:33.890 --> 00:46:36.310
that are genetically
characterized

00:46:36.310 --> 00:46:37.260
in the public domain.

00:46:37.260 --> 00:46:39.170
But it turns out
that Reagan-- who

00:46:39.170 --> 00:46:44.100
I've demonized in my mind in so
many different ways-- in 1984

00:46:44.100 --> 00:46:44.890
a law passed.

00:46:44.890 --> 00:46:45.540
He signed it.

00:46:45.540 --> 00:46:48.070
And what it said was, there
are certain incentives

00:46:48.070 --> 00:46:50.370
for developing drugs
that are off-patent.

00:46:50.370 --> 00:46:53.760
And what that means is that
you can get data exclusivity.

00:46:53.760 --> 00:46:56.800
It means nobody can use
your data for five years

00:46:56.800 --> 00:46:58.510
to market it as a generic.

00:46:58.510 --> 00:47:00.480
But other people
could do the research

00:47:00.480 --> 00:47:02.160
to make the drug
into a medicine.

00:47:02.160 --> 00:47:03.480
They could sell it too.

00:47:03.480 --> 00:47:06.680
So right now, there's
a possibility that MAPS

00:47:06.680 --> 00:47:08.500
and Heffter or
Usona-- which is going

00:47:08.500 --> 00:47:10.530
to work on the
psilocybin-- that we'll be

00:47:10.530 --> 00:47:12.150
the ones that do the research.

00:47:12.150 --> 00:47:13.550
And then, we may
have this period

00:47:13.550 --> 00:47:16.320
of five years-- in
Europe, it's 10 years--

00:47:16.320 --> 00:47:18.680
where we're the only
ones marketing this drug.

00:47:18.680 --> 00:47:23.200
And so, if we make the drug for
$50 and we sell it for $200,

00:47:23.200 --> 00:47:25.910
we can use this money to
pay for more research.

00:47:25.910 --> 00:47:27.780
So now, the story that
I'm telling donors

00:47:27.780 --> 00:47:29.910
is that we have a
sustainability plan,

00:47:29.910 --> 00:47:32.110
that, unlike most
non-profits-- like Feeding

00:47:32.110 --> 00:47:35.352
the Hungry, there's always
going to be more work to do,

00:47:35.352 --> 00:47:36.560
more money you have to raise.

00:47:36.560 --> 00:47:41.140
But we have this opportunity
to make MDMA into a medicine

00:47:41.140 --> 00:47:43.450
and then not need to ask
donors for as much money,

00:47:43.450 --> 00:47:45.610
because we'll be having
some income stream.

00:47:45.610 --> 00:47:48.600
At the same time, we don't
want to really monopolize it.

00:47:48.600 --> 00:47:51.350
So if anybody does want to
make MDMA into a medicine other

00:47:51.350 --> 00:47:52.800
than us, we will help them.

00:47:52.800 --> 00:47:54.830
And so we make our
protocols public.

00:47:54.830 --> 00:47:55.840
Our data is public.

00:47:55.840 --> 00:47:57.630
All of this is trying
to encourage others.

00:47:57.630 --> 00:48:00.670
But so far, we haven't seen
anybody step into it yet.

00:48:00.670 --> 00:48:04.250
And so we have formed
a benefit corporation.

00:48:04.250 --> 00:48:07.920
Selling MDMA and
making money-- it's

00:48:07.920 --> 00:48:10.100
not something that you can
keep inside a nonprofit.

00:48:10.100 --> 00:48:11.520
It's something that's taxable.

00:48:11.520 --> 00:48:14.150
But a lot of people talk about
legalization of marijuana.

00:48:14.150 --> 00:48:16.705
And they say, we don't
want big tobacco.

00:48:16.705 --> 00:48:19.327
Or we don't want big
alcohol marketing marijuana.

00:48:19.327 --> 00:48:20.660
They're going to market to kids.

00:48:20.660 --> 00:48:22.285
They're going to do
all sorts of stuff.

00:48:22.285 --> 00:48:25.230
So having drugs that have
an abuse liability marketed

00:48:25.230 --> 00:48:28.160
by profit-maximizing
corporations

00:48:28.160 --> 00:48:30.530
is kind of worrisome from
a social point-of-view.

00:48:30.530 --> 00:48:33.070
So we've started a benefit
corporation, wholly owned

00:48:33.070 --> 00:48:34.740
by MAPS, no investors.

00:48:34.740 --> 00:48:36.980
And it's not to
maximize profits.

00:48:36.980 --> 00:48:40.610
It's to maximize social
change and social benefit.

00:48:40.610 --> 00:48:44.010
And so that's what
we're showing here.

00:48:44.010 --> 00:48:47.580
Now, you need to evaluate
the benefit corporation

00:48:47.580 --> 00:48:49.130
to public benefit.

00:48:49.130 --> 00:48:50.870
How do you tell that
you're really having

00:48:50.870 --> 00:48:52.290
this benefit corporation?

00:48:52.290 --> 00:48:54.857
And there are no third-party
standards, unfortunately,

00:48:54.857 --> 00:48:56.190
for the pharmaceutical industry.

00:48:56.190 --> 00:48:59.480
So we're creating our own
with some ethicists at UPenn.

00:48:59.480 --> 00:49:04.005
And the challenge now is to
quantify the various principles

00:49:04.005 --> 00:49:05.130
that we're operating under.

00:49:05.130 --> 00:49:07.349
So we're working
on that right now.

00:49:07.349 --> 00:49:09.140
There's a few more
things that we're doing.

00:49:09.140 --> 00:49:11.860
We're also working on
MDMA-assisted psychotherapy

00:49:11.860 --> 00:49:14.640
for autistic adults
with social anxiety.

00:49:14.640 --> 00:49:16.070
And this is a study at UCLA.

00:49:16.070 --> 00:49:18.540
It's a small pilot
study with 12 subjects.

00:49:18.540 --> 00:49:20.740
We just have data
right now from eight.

00:49:20.740 --> 00:49:25.090
But as you can see, this is the
Liebowitz Social Anxiety Scale.

00:49:25.090 --> 00:49:26.420
It's working great.

00:49:26.420 --> 00:49:30.150
And this is something that, in
a sense, Google helped develop.

00:49:30.150 --> 00:49:31.840
Its crowd-sourced
drug development.

00:49:31.840 --> 00:49:36.300
What that means is that somebody
who had autism went to a rave,

00:49:36.300 --> 00:49:37.770
took Ecstasy, and said, wow.

00:49:37.770 --> 00:49:38.780
Now, I can feel.

00:49:38.780 --> 00:49:40.510
Now, I can read body language.

00:49:40.510 --> 00:49:42.710
And they posted their
story on the internet.

00:49:42.710 --> 00:49:45.640
And then, before long,
other people said, oh yeah,

00:49:45.640 --> 00:49:47.030
that happened to me too.

00:49:47.030 --> 00:49:51.640
And then, there was
about 50 or 100 accounts,

00:49:51.640 --> 00:49:54.260
stories on the internet
of people with autism

00:49:54.260 --> 00:49:55.420
saying MDMA helped them.

00:49:55.420 --> 00:49:57.300
And so, a woman--
Alicia Danforth--

00:49:57.300 --> 00:49:59.000
contacted as many as she could.

00:49:59.000 --> 00:50:02.205
And her PhD dissertation
was talking to these people

00:50:02.205 --> 00:50:04.330
through this sort of
crowd-sourced drug development

00:50:04.330 --> 00:50:05.200
idea.

00:50:05.200 --> 00:50:08.610
And then, we used that
as data to the FDA.

00:50:08.610 --> 00:50:10.710
And so, this is really
encouraging data.

00:50:10.710 --> 00:50:13.010
We're also doing a study with
life threatening illness,

00:50:13.010 --> 00:50:14.885
people who have life
threatening illness that

00:50:14.885 --> 00:50:15.850
are scared of dying.

00:50:15.850 --> 00:50:17.434
And there was research with LSD.

00:50:17.434 --> 00:50:18.850
There is research
with psilocybin.

00:50:18.850 --> 00:50:22.980
And our research with MDMA
is now at San Anselmo.

00:50:22.980 --> 00:50:24.670
This is Dr. Phil Wolfson.

00:50:24.670 --> 00:50:26.860
It's a double-blind
study, 18 participants.

00:50:26.860 --> 00:50:30.250
We've already enrolled five.

00:50:30.250 --> 00:50:32.690
This was a front-page "San
Francisco Chronicle" article

00:50:32.690 --> 00:50:34.670
about it.

00:50:34.670 --> 00:50:38.880
And this is a study
that just happened.

00:50:38.880 --> 00:50:41.170
We just got approval
for this on Tuesday.

00:50:41.170 --> 00:50:43.760
This is the first
study in association

00:50:43.760 --> 00:50:46.640
informally with VA therapists.

00:50:46.640 --> 00:50:49.484
And when the VA was think-- as I
said, the Department of Defense

00:50:49.484 --> 00:50:52.150
wasn't so excited about us doing
work with active-duty soldiers.

00:50:52.150 --> 00:50:56.870
But the VA, they were thinking,
well, where do we blend MDMA?

00:50:56.870 --> 00:51:00.200
And they had a program that
was called Cognitive Behavioral

00:51:00.200 --> 00:51:02.680
Conjoint Therapy,
where "conjoint" means

00:51:02.680 --> 00:51:04.030
couples therapy.

00:51:04.030 --> 00:51:08.340
And they thought, OK, MDMA--
hug drug, love drug, couples.

00:51:08.340 --> 00:51:09.630
Let's work it there.

00:51:09.630 --> 00:51:11.280
So they introduced
us to the person

00:51:11.280 --> 00:51:14.150
that was the VA therapist
who was working with this.

00:51:14.150 --> 00:51:16.270
And we've decided to blend.

00:51:16.270 --> 00:51:19.690
We're going to pay for the study
as a sort of prime the pump

00:51:19.690 --> 00:51:20.650
with the VA.

00:51:20.650 --> 00:51:23.590
But what we wanted to do was
give both members of the couple

00:51:23.590 --> 00:51:24.750
MDMA.

00:51:24.750 --> 00:51:28.040
And on Tuesday,
the FDA said yes.

00:51:28.040 --> 00:51:31.230
And this is the first
instance that this modern wave

00:51:31.230 --> 00:51:34.541
of psychedelic research-- it
began in 1990 with the DMT

00:51:34.541 --> 00:51:35.040
research.

00:51:35.040 --> 00:51:36.581
And it's always been
single patients.

00:51:36.581 --> 00:51:39.810
So now, we have a chance to
actually give two people--

00:51:39.810 --> 00:51:42.500
and that will hopefully help
us move, eventually, also

00:51:42.500 --> 00:51:44.550
to look at group psychotherapy.

00:51:44.550 --> 00:51:46.300
Now, we're also doing
work with marijuana.

00:51:46.300 --> 00:51:48.867
I just want to say
that right now it's

00:51:48.867 --> 00:51:50.700
more difficult to do
research with marijuana

00:51:50.700 --> 00:51:52.940
than psychedelics.

00:51:52.940 --> 00:51:56.000
The reason is that we have our
own supplies of psychedelics.

00:51:56.000 --> 00:51:57.800
But there is
marijuana everywhere.

00:51:57.800 --> 00:52:00.320
But the only
DEA-licensed marijuana

00:52:00.320 --> 00:52:02.150
is owned by the National
Institute on Drug

00:52:02.150 --> 00:52:04.880
Abuse, the agency that's
about what's bad with drugs.

00:52:04.880 --> 00:52:07.130
And if you want to look at
what's good with marijuana,

00:52:07.130 --> 00:52:09.250
they don't really want
to give it to you.

00:52:09.250 --> 00:52:11.660
So we have tried for six years.

00:52:11.660 --> 00:52:14.300
And we finally have been
able to get permission

00:52:14.300 --> 00:52:18.620
for a study of marijuana
for PTSD in 76 US veterans.

00:52:18.620 --> 00:52:20.410
Marijuana is a
palliative treatment.

00:52:20.410 --> 00:52:22.250
It helps people not
have nightmares.

00:52:22.250 --> 00:52:23.680
It helps them be
present, focused.

00:52:23.680 --> 00:52:25.054
But it doesn't
solve the problem.

00:52:25.054 --> 00:52:28.154
People need to take
marijuana every day.

00:52:28.154 --> 00:52:29.820
But it still is helpful
for some people.

00:52:29.820 --> 00:52:32.250
And so, we're sort of
becoming the experts in PTSD,

00:52:32.250 --> 00:52:35.420
as well as experts in MDMA.

00:52:35.420 --> 00:52:40.970
And so, Sanjay Gupta did a
series of stories on marijuana.

00:52:40.970 --> 00:52:45.550
We were a big focus of
"Weed 3," our project.

00:52:45.550 --> 00:52:47.620
Basically, this is
just to show that we're

00:52:47.620 --> 00:52:49.750
comparing some
groups that get THC,

00:52:49.750 --> 00:52:52.160
some groups that get CBD
containing marijuana,

00:52:52.160 --> 00:52:54.590
and one group that gets
both, and then one that

00:52:54.590 --> 00:52:57.100
gets a placebo.

00:52:57.100 --> 00:53:01.250
And we got a $2.1 million grant
from the state of Colorado

00:53:01.250 --> 00:53:02.310
for this study.

00:53:02.310 --> 00:53:04.670
The state of Colorado has
taken in over $100 million

00:53:04.670 --> 00:53:07.060
in taxes for marijuana.

00:53:07.060 --> 00:53:09.810
And they put out $9 million
for marijuana research.

00:53:09.810 --> 00:53:12.010
And they were willing
to give us $2.1 million.

00:53:12.010 --> 00:53:13.840
This is a protest.

00:53:13.840 --> 00:53:16.800
We're also suing the DEA.

00:53:16.800 --> 00:53:18.582
Covington &amp; Burling
is a big DC law firm.

00:53:18.582 --> 00:53:20.290
They've agreed to take
the case pro bono.

00:53:20.290 --> 00:53:21.990
We're trying to
break the monopoly.

00:53:21.990 --> 00:53:23.660
And this is a
protest that we had

00:53:23.660 --> 00:53:26.530
on the lawn of the
DEA headquarters

00:53:26.530 --> 00:53:28.915
saying, give us a
license to grow pot.

00:53:28.915 --> 00:53:30.790
Basically, it's the same
with the MDMA story.

00:53:30.790 --> 00:53:33.964
We won the administrative
law judge lawsuit.

00:53:33.964 --> 00:53:36.380
But then, the head of the DEA
rejected the recommendation.

00:53:36.380 --> 00:53:38.430
So we're continuing to try.

00:53:38.430 --> 00:53:41.060
And now, we get to Burning Man.

00:53:41.060 --> 00:53:44.500
What are the potential
reasons for backlash

00:53:44.500 --> 00:53:46.640
that would block our progress?

00:53:46.640 --> 00:53:51.670
And it used to be, the
initial backlash in the '60s

00:53:51.670 --> 00:53:53.760
was about political reasons,
about these hippies,

00:53:53.760 --> 00:53:57.490
the counterculture, the Beatles
doing LSD, against the war,

00:53:57.490 --> 00:53:59.770
make love not war.

00:53:59.770 --> 00:54:01.440
The backlash was political.

00:54:01.440 --> 00:54:02.600
But that has faded now.

00:54:02.600 --> 00:54:04.690
And so now, the main
reason of backlash

00:54:04.690 --> 00:54:07.340
would be parents worried
about their kids.

00:54:07.340 --> 00:54:10.390
And an example is,
at Burning Man,

00:54:10.390 --> 00:54:11.830
at festivals where
people do lots

00:54:11.830 --> 00:54:14.910
of psychedelics, a bunch of
people are not prepared for it.

00:54:14.910 --> 00:54:18.160
And what happens is they end
up either getting tranquilized

00:54:18.160 --> 00:54:19.430
or getting arrested.

00:54:19.430 --> 00:54:21.260
And so, we've started
the Zendo Project

00:54:21.260 --> 00:54:24.330
to do psychedelic
harm-reduction at festivals

00:54:24.330 --> 00:54:25.570
all over the world.

00:54:25.570 --> 00:54:27.990
And we've picked some of the
more well-known ones, Burning

00:54:27.990 --> 00:54:32.220
Man, Boom Festival in Portugal,
Envision in Costa Rica.

00:54:32.220 --> 00:54:35.250
And we provide psychedelic
therapists and psychologists,

00:54:35.250 --> 00:54:37.900
psychiatrists, to
help people, as a way

00:54:37.900 --> 00:54:42.410
of trying to reduce the
costs and reduce the fears.

00:54:42.410 --> 00:54:44.180
This is complicated
by the fact that there

00:54:44.180 --> 00:54:46.263
is a law against harm
reduction with psychedelics.

00:54:46.263 --> 00:54:48.760
It's called the RAVE
Act, Reducing America's

00:54:48.760 --> 00:54:51.440
Vulnerability to Ecstasy.

00:54:51.440 --> 00:54:54.010
You can't have too much
Ecstasy in America.

00:54:54.010 --> 00:54:55.130
So it's a problem.

00:54:55.130 --> 00:54:58.280
But we're working
politically to get that over.

00:54:58.280 --> 00:55:00.670
This is our training
group at Burning Man.

00:55:00.670 --> 00:55:03.050
We had 180 people
wanted to get training

00:55:03.050 --> 00:55:06.880
in how to help people go
through a difficult trip.

00:55:06.880 --> 00:55:08.810
To locate where we
were-- so the Burning

00:55:08.810 --> 00:55:12.760
Man Organization is worried.

00:55:12.760 --> 00:55:14.910
But they let people do
stuff-- all sorts of stuff

00:55:14.910 --> 00:55:16.260
obviously-- in their villages.

00:55:16.260 --> 00:55:17.620
So we do this in our villages.

00:55:17.620 --> 00:55:19.290
We're not formally connected.

00:55:19.290 --> 00:55:22.920
But we're getting more and
more connected informally.

00:55:22.920 --> 00:55:25.625
And so we had to put
a flag up for people

00:55:25.625 --> 00:55:26.750
to recognize where we were.

00:55:26.750 --> 00:55:29.750
And so to have our own
Zendo flag at Burning Man,

00:55:29.750 --> 00:55:33.270
it felt like I was an
explorer, planting my flag,

00:55:33.270 --> 00:55:34.810
like we had our
own little country.

00:55:34.810 --> 00:55:38.860
I felt so accepted to have
our little Zendo flag there.

00:55:38.860 --> 00:55:42.540
And this is to show
you what's possible.

00:55:42.540 --> 00:55:45.870
This just took place-- Burning
Man on the Washington DC Mall.

00:55:45.870 --> 00:55:47.460
This took place in November.

00:55:47.460 --> 00:55:51.390
We aligned ourselves with the
local Burning Man community.

00:55:51.390 --> 00:55:55.270
And we actually-- you can't
just have a party on the Mall.

00:55:55.270 --> 00:55:57.380
You have to be upset
about something.

00:55:57.380 --> 00:55:58.160
[LAUGHTER]

00:55:58.160 --> 00:56:00.910
You have to protest something.

00:56:00.910 --> 00:56:05.870
So this, we timed it for the
Drug Policy Alliance Conference

00:56:05.870 --> 00:56:06.930
in Washington, DC.

00:56:06.930 --> 00:56:09.390
So this is a protest
against the drug war.

00:56:09.390 --> 00:56:11.140
We actually did though have DJs.

00:56:11.140 --> 00:56:12.840
We had dancing all night.

00:56:12.840 --> 00:56:15.640
We had the Zendo team there.

00:56:15.640 --> 00:56:19.040
This was right between the
White House and the Washington

00:56:19.040 --> 00:56:20.100
Monument.

00:56:20.100 --> 00:56:22.450
And the most exhilarating
moment for me

00:56:22.450 --> 00:56:26.610
was around 4:30 in the morning,
dancing with David Bronner.

00:56:26.610 --> 00:56:28.270
It was like we
thought, we did it.

00:56:28.270 --> 00:56:29.245
We got the permits.

00:56:29.245 --> 00:56:30.120
Everything's working.

00:56:30.120 --> 00:56:32.030
There's over 1,000
people at the burn.

00:56:32.030 --> 00:56:36.870
And at that moment, the
DJ put on Jimi Hendrix

00:56:36.870 --> 00:56:40.080
playing the national
anthem from Woodstock,

00:56:40.080 --> 00:56:41.990
and playing it so loud
that you could hear

00:56:41.990 --> 00:56:43.950
the music in the White House.

00:56:43.950 --> 00:56:46.540
And we thought, wow, here's
from counterculture Woodstock.

00:56:46.540 --> 00:56:48.850
Now, we're doing Burning Man
with a permit, completely

00:56:48.850 --> 00:56:50.861
legally, on the Washington Mall.

00:56:50.861 --> 00:56:52.360
And the little
temple structure that

00:56:52.360 --> 00:56:57.690
burned, once it burned down, it
burned to reveal a jail cell.

00:56:57.690 --> 00:57:00.260
And then, the jail
cell burned down too.

00:57:00.260 --> 00:57:03.810
And so, now, this
is our 30th year.

00:57:03.810 --> 00:57:07.040
In April is our
30th anniversary.

00:57:07.040 --> 00:57:08.567
We're asking people
to have dinners.

00:57:08.567 --> 00:57:10.650
We're looking at, what
happened with gay marriage?

00:57:10.650 --> 00:57:11.360
How did that work?

00:57:11.360 --> 00:57:12.610
What happened with gay rights?

00:57:12.610 --> 00:57:13.400
People came out.

00:57:13.400 --> 00:57:15.514
People didn't they
knew gay people.

00:57:15.514 --> 00:57:16.930
People, the same
thing, don't know

00:57:16.930 --> 00:57:18.787
they know people who
have done psychedelics.

00:57:18.787 --> 00:57:20.370
So we're asking
people to have dinners

00:57:20.370 --> 00:57:23.090
in home private settings
and invite their friends

00:57:23.090 --> 00:57:25.500
and just tell stories
about what psychedelics

00:57:25.500 --> 00:57:26.310
have meant to them.

00:57:26.310 --> 00:57:28.664
So some of you may be
interested in considering that.

00:57:28.664 --> 00:57:30.080
And then, we're
asking at the end,

00:57:30.080 --> 00:57:31.660
for people-- if they
want to donate--

00:57:31.660 --> 00:57:34.210
to help us have
a legal drug deal

00:57:34.210 --> 00:57:38.720
and contribute to our
$400,000 cost for the MDMA.

00:57:38.720 --> 00:57:43.990
And we're also having a
conference in Oakland in 2017.

00:57:43.990 --> 00:57:45.580
It's the third
iteration of this.

00:57:45.580 --> 00:57:47.080
We're having
psychedelic researchers

00:57:47.080 --> 00:57:49.650
from all over the world,
psychedelic science.

00:57:49.650 --> 00:57:51.320
You're all welcome
to come to it.

00:57:51.320 --> 00:57:52.650
And this is the final slide.

00:57:52.650 --> 00:57:54.310
This is what I want
to leave you with.

00:57:54.310 --> 00:57:56.980
In 2010, I got a call
from the Pentagon.

00:57:56.980 --> 00:57:59.880
And it was from a
brigadier general.

00:57:59.880 --> 00:58:02.560
She was the highest-ranking
psychiatrist in the military.

00:58:02.560 --> 00:58:04.670
She was in charge
of PTSD research.

00:58:04.670 --> 00:58:07.240
And she heard about
our study with MDMA.

00:58:07.240 --> 00:58:09.030
And she called and
said, what's going on?

00:58:09.030 --> 00:58:10.890
We have a terrible
problem with PTSD.

00:58:10.890 --> 00:58:14.010
And so we have since shared
information with her.

00:58:14.010 --> 00:58:15.510
And she's been
willing to go public.

00:58:15.510 --> 00:58:19.160
She's now no longer in the DEA.

00:58:19.160 --> 00:58:22.490
But she works here in
New York for the mayor.

00:58:22.490 --> 00:58:24.509
And she said this.
"When it comes

00:58:24.509 --> 00:58:26.050
to the health and
well-being of those

00:58:26.050 --> 00:58:28.330
who serve, we should leave
our politics at the door

00:58:28.330 --> 00:58:30.570
and not be afraid
to follow the data.

00:58:30.570 --> 00:58:33.670
There is now an evidence
base for this MDMA therapy

00:58:33.670 --> 00:58:36.660
and a plausible story about what
may be going on in the brain

00:58:36.660 --> 00:58:38.420
to account for the effects."

00:58:38.420 --> 00:58:40.989
So you can see that
our society is really--

00:58:40.989 --> 00:58:42.530
I think-- opening
up to psychedelics.

00:58:42.530 --> 00:58:44.650
We have a chance to
integrate medically and then

00:58:44.650 --> 00:58:47.787
broaden, hopefully,
into more legalization

00:58:47.787 --> 00:58:50.120
and then, hopefully, have
millions and tens of millions,

00:58:50.120 --> 00:58:51.578
hundreds of millions
of people have

00:58:51.578 --> 00:58:53.950
these spiritual experiences.

00:58:53.950 --> 00:58:58.202
And before you know it, world
peace and the Google Department

00:58:58.202 --> 00:58:59.910
of World Peace will
hopefully participate

00:58:59.910 --> 00:59:01.880
in some way or another.

00:59:01.880 --> 00:59:03.346
Thank you very much.

00:59:03.346 --> 00:59:05.692
[APPLAUSE]

00:59:10.808 --> 00:59:11.307
Yeah.

00:59:15.630 --> 00:59:18.010
OK, so any questions?

00:59:18.010 --> 00:59:19.730
Julie, yeah?

00:59:19.730 --> 00:59:24.010
AUDIENCE: Dr. Doblin, thank you
for mentioning this openness

00:59:24.010 --> 00:59:27.450
issue with psilocybin that Dr.
McLean showed and that openness

00:59:27.450 --> 00:59:29.352
being important for
changing behavior.

00:59:29.352 --> 00:59:31.560
But this is the first I've
heard about openness being

00:59:31.560 --> 00:59:33.340
measured in MDMA protocol.

00:59:33.340 --> 00:59:35.590
So I was wondering if you
could talk a little bit more

00:59:35.590 --> 00:59:36.170
about that.

00:59:36.170 --> 00:59:37.340
RICK DOBLIN: Yeah.

00:59:37.340 --> 00:59:41.016
Well, the psilocybin research
and the MDMA research,

00:59:41.016 --> 00:59:42.140
we learned from each other.

00:59:42.140 --> 00:59:46.690
So we saw that there was
a benefit in openness.

00:59:46.690 --> 00:59:49.160
So we started using
the NEO in our studies.

00:59:49.160 --> 00:59:51.700
And it's been a
long time, trying

00:59:51.700 --> 00:59:53.120
to get the papers written.

00:59:53.120 --> 00:59:55.850
But we now are using
the same personality

00:59:55.850 --> 00:59:57.489
measures that were used there.

00:59:57.489 --> 00:59:59.030
And we're getting
really good results

00:59:59.030 --> 01:00:01.900
in both the Boulder study and
also in the Charleston study

01:00:01.900 --> 01:00:03.820
with veterans.

01:00:03.820 --> 01:00:05.280
So it's a good collaboration.

01:00:05.280 --> 01:00:08.100
So the psychedelic researchers
are really not competing.

01:00:08.100 --> 01:00:10.030
There sort of is a
competition in my mind, who

01:00:10.030 --> 01:00:12.190
gets their drug approved first.

01:00:12.190 --> 01:00:13.690
But we're trying
to help each other.

01:00:13.690 --> 01:00:14.940
AUDIENCE: Healthy competition.

01:00:14.940 --> 01:00:17.220
RICK DOBLIN: A healthy
competition, yeah.

01:00:17.220 --> 01:00:18.000
Yeah?

01:00:18.000 --> 01:00:19.875
AUDIENCE: We've all
heard songs about popping

01:00:19.875 --> 01:00:21.680
Molly in the club.

01:00:21.680 --> 01:00:23.620
So do you think that
hedonistic attitudes

01:00:23.620 --> 01:00:26.510
about how MDMA is like the
perfect way to spend the night

01:00:26.510 --> 01:00:31.500
can coexist peacefully with
therapeutic mindsets about--

01:00:31.500 --> 01:00:32.900
RICK DOBLIN: Yes, I do actually.

01:00:32.900 --> 01:00:36.640
So I think that the problem
with hedonistic approaches

01:00:36.640 --> 01:00:38.920
is that people are
really looking only

01:00:38.920 --> 01:00:40.820
for the good experiences.

01:00:40.820 --> 01:00:42.490
And they're missing
out on the fact

01:00:42.490 --> 01:00:44.320
that difficult
experiences are ones where

01:00:44.320 --> 01:00:46.540
people can grow from as well.

01:00:46.540 --> 01:00:47.530
And that's a danger.

01:00:47.530 --> 01:00:49.930
And so we've talked to
different people who

01:00:49.930 --> 01:00:52.930
have said that they took MDMA
in recreational settings,

01:00:52.930 --> 01:00:54.602
and then past trauma came up.

01:00:54.602 --> 01:00:56.560
And within one week, we
had two different women

01:00:56.560 --> 01:00:57.720
talk to us about this.

01:00:57.720 --> 01:01:00.320
And one woman said,
I was with friends.

01:01:00.320 --> 01:01:02.130
And they were sympathetic.

01:01:02.130 --> 01:01:03.400
And we went off into a corner.

01:01:03.400 --> 01:01:04.775
And I talked about
what happened.

01:01:04.775 --> 01:01:05.730
I worked through it.

01:01:05.730 --> 01:01:08.310
And then I was able to feel
better and go back to a party.

01:01:08.310 --> 01:01:11.000
And another woman said, I
was with a bunch of people.

01:01:11.000 --> 01:01:12.390
We were all going to have fun.

01:01:12.390 --> 01:01:14.765
And I thought I would take
everybody down by telling them

01:01:14.765 --> 01:01:15.560
about the serious stuff.

01:01:15.560 --> 01:01:17.080
So I tried to stuff my feelings.

01:01:17.080 --> 01:01:19.520
And now, it's weeks later
and I'm feeling worse.

01:01:19.520 --> 01:01:23.180
So I think there's problems with
this, quote, "hedonistic use."

01:01:23.180 --> 01:01:26.870
But I would say that
the celebratory use--

01:01:26.870 --> 01:01:29.150
like is a lot of Burning
Man and other things--

01:01:29.150 --> 01:01:32.270
that that can be very
healing and very spiritual.

01:01:32.270 --> 01:01:35.050
So I think we tend to
denigrate recreational use.

01:01:35.050 --> 01:01:37.310
It's somehow lower.

01:01:37.310 --> 01:01:41.040
But I think that it's
people's attitudes.

01:01:41.040 --> 01:01:42.660
When you open up
your mind, and if you

01:01:42.660 --> 01:01:45.090
say I only want a
good part, I only

01:01:45.090 --> 01:01:47.620
want the happy spectrum
of what's going on,

01:01:47.620 --> 01:01:49.722
you're setting yourself
up for disaster.

01:01:49.722 --> 01:01:51.680
And I think that a lot
of the young people that

01:01:51.680 --> 01:01:54.770
use it hedonistically, it's
they don't know any different.

01:01:54.770 --> 01:01:56.990
They don't know that
it's a therapeutic drug.

01:01:56.990 --> 01:01:59.080
They only know of
it as a party drug.

01:01:59.080 --> 01:02:01.470
So I think, as we develop
the therapeutic use

01:02:01.470 --> 01:02:03.920
and as psychedelic
clinics set up,

01:02:03.920 --> 01:02:07.160
people will be able to have a
deeper understanding of what

01:02:07.160 --> 01:02:08.720
these drugs really do.

01:02:08.720 --> 01:02:11.500
And also, as the rules
about harm reduction change,

01:02:11.500 --> 01:02:14.940
hopefully we'll have
people at big festivals,

01:02:14.940 --> 01:02:17.569
at even big clubs-- I mean,
they already have medical staff.

01:02:17.569 --> 01:02:19.110
And if you could
have somebody that's

01:02:19.110 --> 01:02:22.060
trained to help people if they
have a difficult experience,

01:02:22.060 --> 01:02:23.360
then I think we'll have a lot.

01:02:23.360 --> 01:02:25.830
But I do think that,
culturally, we're

01:02:25.830 --> 01:02:29.650
past the point where tragedies
from the hedonistic use

01:02:29.650 --> 01:02:31.026
will doom the medical use.

01:02:31.026 --> 01:02:31.900
That was a big thing.

01:02:31.900 --> 01:02:34.670
And I think now, the data
about the medical use

01:02:34.670 --> 01:02:38.850
is so compelling and the need
is so great that, now, I'm

01:02:38.850 --> 01:02:39.830
not worried about it.

01:02:39.830 --> 01:02:42.100
But I do think we need to
redefine recreational use

01:02:42.100 --> 01:02:44.810
and not just think
of it as totally

01:02:44.810 --> 01:02:48.500
negative and hedonistic
and casual and reckless.

01:02:48.500 --> 01:02:49.200
Yeah?

01:02:49.200 --> 01:02:49.825
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:02:49.825 --> 01:02:50.548
Can you--

01:02:50.548 --> 01:02:51.689
RICK DOBLIN: Oh.

01:02:51.689 --> 01:02:53.980
AUDIENCE: Thanks so much for
coming and speaking to us.

01:02:53.980 --> 01:02:55.880
And I have a question
in a similar vein,

01:02:55.880 --> 01:02:57.939
where the data definitely
speaks for itself.

01:02:57.939 --> 01:02:59.480
And it makes total
sense that there's

01:02:59.480 --> 01:03:03.340
good medical use and really
[INAUDIBLE] to work out.

01:03:03.340 --> 01:03:07.185
But at some point, politically,
some aspiring politician

01:03:07.185 --> 01:03:10.490
may think, oh, this is
something that I can just

01:03:10.490 --> 01:03:12.237
go after and say,
hey, drugs are bad.

01:03:12.237 --> 01:03:12.820
It's terrible.

01:03:12.820 --> 01:03:14.210
And this is what's
going to get me elected.

01:03:14.210 --> 01:03:16.300
So what do you really
think is that critical mass

01:03:16.300 --> 01:03:18.240
that we have to reach
to really be able to be

01:03:18.240 --> 01:03:19.270
that this is mainstream?

01:03:19.270 --> 01:03:22.580
And it won't be politically
savvy to say, no, MDMA,

01:03:22.580 --> 01:03:24.410
LSD, psilocybin is terrible.

01:03:24.410 --> 01:03:26.490
And you guys should keep
your kids away from it.

01:03:26.490 --> 01:03:27.824
And you shouldn't be doing this.

01:03:27.824 --> 01:03:29.573
RICK DOBLIN: Yes,
that's a great question.

01:03:29.573 --> 01:03:31.540
And there are people like
that saying that now.

01:03:31.540 --> 01:03:32.706
But there are less and less.

01:03:32.706 --> 01:03:34.950
I think the critical
turning point

01:03:34.950 --> 01:03:39.039
is going to be when FDA says yes
to making these into medicines.

01:03:39.039 --> 01:03:40.080
And that'll be six years.

01:03:40.080 --> 01:03:42.450
So I think it's perilous,
you could say, between now

01:03:42.450 --> 01:03:43.210
and then.

01:03:43.210 --> 01:03:45.910
Another turning point
is going to be sooner.

01:03:45.910 --> 01:03:48.560
In this coming year, when
we negotiate with FDA

01:03:48.560 --> 01:03:51.250
and the Heffter people
negotiate about psilocybin

01:03:51.250 --> 01:03:53.500
and move to Phase
3-- once they say,

01:03:53.500 --> 01:03:57.000
yes, you can go to Phase 3,
that's a strong endorsement.

01:03:57.000 --> 01:03:59.750
And then, I think it will
not be possible to block

01:03:59.750 --> 01:04:02.032
what we're doing, at least
until it gets to the point

01:04:02.032 --> 01:04:02.990
where we have the data.

01:04:02.990 --> 01:04:05.760
And then, the question is,
does it become approved?

01:04:05.760 --> 01:04:08.300
But I think this idea
of politicians saying,

01:04:08.300 --> 01:04:10.710
let's ramp up the
drug war-- that there

01:04:10.710 --> 01:04:13.900
is rare bipartisan
anything in Washington.

01:04:13.900 --> 01:04:18.470
But there is a fair amount
of bipartisan recognition

01:04:18.470 --> 01:04:22.620
that mass incarceration has
been a disaster for America

01:04:22.620 --> 01:04:25.890
and has been incredibly
racist, incredibly destructive.

01:04:25.890 --> 01:04:29.030
And you know, the
Chinese say, crisis

01:04:29.030 --> 01:04:30.720
is danger and opportunity.

01:04:30.720 --> 01:04:34.300
So right now, the fact
that heroin and phentynol

01:04:34.300 --> 01:04:36.475
are now used by more
and more white people

01:04:36.475 --> 01:04:37.850
and there is more
and more deaths

01:04:37.850 --> 01:04:41.920
from opiate addiction, that is
changing people's attitudes.

01:04:41.920 --> 01:04:44.820
And now, there is a more
compassionate approach,

01:04:44.820 --> 01:04:46.550
in a lot of places,
towards treatment

01:04:46.550 --> 01:04:48.180
instead of incarceration.

01:04:48.180 --> 01:04:50.260
So I think those
voices that are saying,

01:04:50.260 --> 01:04:54.230
ramp up the drug
war-- they don't

01:04:54.230 --> 01:04:55.600
have as much power anymore.

01:04:55.600 --> 01:04:59.420
But I am sensitive to
the potential backlash.

01:04:59.420 --> 01:05:05.270
But I feel fairly hopeful that
we will be able to continue.

01:05:05.270 --> 01:05:08.850
But it is still risky.

01:05:08.850 --> 01:05:11.750
And the other part of
it is the veterans.

01:05:11.750 --> 01:05:15.380
So when you talk about
healing people that

01:05:15.380 --> 01:05:18.080
are held in high
esteem by our culture--

01:05:18.080 --> 01:05:20.320
I'm not trying to say I'm
pro-war and everything

01:05:20.320 --> 01:05:21.960
the military does is great.

01:05:21.960 --> 01:05:24.270
But by healing
veterans-- veterans

01:05:24.270 --> 01:05:28.370
are a counter-force to
the police, to the DEA.

01:05:28.370 --> 01:05:32.460
And in fact, in our study, we've
said, for political reasons,

01:05:32.460 --> 01:05:34.920
we're going to change
the title of the study.

01:05:34.920 --> 01:05:36.860
It's going to be
Veterans, Firefighters,

01:05:36.860 --> 01:05:38.084
and Police Officers.

01:05:38.084 --> 01:05:38.785
[LAUGHTER]

01:05:38.785 --> 01:05:40.910
We didn't think we'd get
any firefighters or police

01:05:40.910 --> 01:05:41.409
officers.

01:05:41.409 --> 01:05:44.130
But of the 26 people,
we've got 22 veterans,

01:05:44.130 --> 01:05:47.830
three firefighters-- including
one who was here at 9/11.

01:05:47.830 --> 01:05:51.394
And we had one police
officer volunteer.

01:05:51.394 --> 01:05:53.060
And so, when you think
about it, there's

01:05:53.060 --> 01:05:56.580
very few jobs in America that
are as traumatizing as being

01:05:56.580 --> 01:05:58.340
a police officer.

01:05:58.340 --> 01:06:01.250
And because of
the drug war, I've

01:06:01.250 --> 01:06:03.810
not had much compassion
for the police.

01:06:03.810 --> 01:06:07.250
I felt like, I'm the prey
and they're the hunter.

01:06:07.250 --> 01:06:10.820
But to try to get out
of that kind of mindset,

01:06:10.820 --> 01:06:14.640
I think showing to the police
even that MDMA therapy can

01:06:14.640 --> 01:06:17.160
help them in their
own-- there is just

01:06:17.160 --> 01:06:21.200
a lot of terrible situations
that police have to see.

01:06:21.200 --> 01:06:23.220
So we're doing what
we can to cross

01:06:23.220 --> 01:06:25.370
those divides and
undercut arguments

01:06:25.370 --> 01:06:28.950
that we need to protect the kids
or we need to protect America

01:06:28.950 --> 01:06:33.130
by ramping up the drug war.

01:06:33.130 --> 01:06:35.412
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I was
wondering, how broad

01:06:35.412 --> 01:06:37.296
is the term "psychedelic"?

01:06:37.296 --> 01:06:40.450
In the sense of, what are
some of the differences

01:06:40.450 --> 01:06:43.228
in the mechanisms and effects
when you talk about LSD

01:06:43.228 --> 01:06:45.550
or psilocybin or MDMA?

01:06:45.550 --> 01:06:47.540
RICK DOBLIN: Yeah,
great question.

01:06:47.540 --> 01:06:51.130
So I would say that
there is a group of drugs

01:06:51.130 --> 01:06:52.950
that we call the
classic psychedelics.

01:06:52.950 --> 01:06:56.300
And those are like LSD,
mescaline from peyote,

01:06:56.300 --> 01:06:59.130
mushrooms, ayahuasca, ibogaine.

01:06:59.130 --> 01:07:02.110
And there's been
incredible research

01:07:02.110 --> 01:07:05.124
now with brain scans with
people under the influence

01:07:05.124 --> 01:07:05.790
of psychedelics.

01:07:05.790 --> 01:07:07.910
So we have not just
psychedelic psychotherapy,

01:07:07.910 --> 01:07:10.250
but psychedelic
neuroscience is happening.

01:07:10.250 --> 01:07:12.240
And so there's two
different things

01:07:12.240 --> 01:07:14.090
that happen with the
classic psychedelics

01:07:14.090 --> 01:07:16.930
and then what's happened with
MDMA and drugs like that.

01:07:16.930 --> 01:07:20.370
And the difference is that,
with the classic psychedelics,

01:07:20.370 --> 01:07:23.400
there's a network in the
brain called the Default Mode

01:07:23.400 --> 01:07:24.250
Network.

01:07:24.250 --> 01:07:26.240
And that's more
or less identified

01:07:26.240 --> 01:07:27.570
as the ego structures.

01:07:27.570 --> 01:07:30.140
So it's like, when you're not
doing anything in particular,

01:07:30.140 --> 01:07:31.806
you're kind of scanning
the environment,

01:07:31.806 --> 01:07:33.770
you're looking for
what's important to you

01:07:33.770 --> 01:07:35.830
for your different
hierarchy of needs,

01:07:35.830 --> 01:07:38.210
but you're kind of ego-focused,
centered in yourself.

01:07:38.210 --> 01:07:40.140
And there's actually
so much information

01:07:40.140 --> 01:07:41.879
that we're perceiving
all the time,

01:07:41.879 --> 01:07:43.420
but we don't pay
attention to it all.

01:07:43.420 --> 01:07:44.680
It would be overwhelming.

01:07:44.680 --> 01:07:47.920
So the Default Mode Network
filters out everything

01:07:47.920 --> 01:07:49.760
that you think is not important.

01:07:49.760 --> 01:07:52.186
Like there's noises of
the air conditioning.

01:07:52.186 --> 01:07:54.560
There's noises that we're not
really paying attention to.

01:07:54.560 --> 01:07:56.570
So what the classic
psychedelics do

01:07:56.570 --> 01:08:00.080
is they weaken the
Default Mode Network.

01:08:00.080 --> 01:08:04.210
And they permit a flood
of perceptions to emerge.

01:08:04.210 --> 01:08:08.570
The woman, Amanda Fielding--
she heads the Beckley

01:08:08.570 --> 01:08:09.540
Foundation in England.

01:08:09.540 --> 01:08:11.150
She funded this research.

01:08:11.150 --> 01:08:13.530
And what I'm so
proud of her for is

01:08:13.530 --> 01:08:17.109
that she thought, since the
'60s, from her experiences

01:08:17.109 --> 01:08:20.350
with LSD, that LSD must increase
blood flow in the brain.

01:08:20.350 --> 01:08:22.649
It must increase your activity.

01:08:22.649 --> 01:08:23.800
But actually it doesn't.

01:08:23.800 --> 01:08:27.760
It decreases activity in
these Default Mode Networks.

01:08:27.760 --> 01:08:29.600
MDMA doesn't really do that.

01:08:29.600 --> 01:08:32.600
What MDMA does is
it reduces activity

01:08:32.600 --> 01:08:34.790
in the amygdala, which
is the fear processing

01:08:34.790 --> 01:08:35.770
part of the brain.

01:08:35.770 --> 01:08:39.630
And it enhances activity in
the frontal cortex, where

01:08:39.630 --> 01:08:41.490
you put things in associations.

01:08:41.490 --> 01:08:44.170
So you have a reduced
fear about trauma.

01:08:44.170 --> 01:08:47.890
And then, when you're
able to recall the memory,

01:08:47.890 --> 01:08:50.149
you can really set
it in to the past

01:08:50.149 --> 01:08:52.819
instead of constantly
intruding on the present.

01:08:52.819 --> 01:08:56.403
And MDMA doesn't
dissolve the ego the way

01:08:56.403 --> 01:08:57.569
the classic psychedelics do.

01:08:57.569 --> 01:09:00.140
But it helps people feel
so grounded and centered

01:09:00.140 --> 01:09:03.870
in themself that, then, they
can see the wider world.

01:09:03.870 --> 01:09:08.010
Stan Groff has talked
about it as, you're

01:09:08.010 --> 01:09:10.840
transparent to the transcendent.

01:09:10.840 --> 01:09:12.439
And that's more like MDMA.

01:09:12.439 --> 01:09:14.439
You become transparent
to the transcendent.

01:09:14.439 --> 01:09:17.200
Whereas LSD sort of
dissolves everything that

01:09:17.200 --> 01:09:20.390
keeps you feeling separate.

01:09:20.390 --> 01:09:22.510
Yeah.

01:09:22.510 --> 01:09:23.394
Great.

01:09:23.394 --> 01:09:24.600
Any questions?

01:09:24.600 --> 01:09:26.399
OK, I guess that's it.

